.broadwayworld.com/australia-melbourne/article/Kenny-Sebastian-Announces-First-Australian-Shows-20180809|title=Kenny Sebastian Announces First Australian Shows|last=BWW News Desk|date=9 August 2018|work=Broadway World}}</ref> In 2017, he produced an hour-long comedy special for [[Amazon Prime]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/amazon-inks-ground-breaking-deal-14-indian-stand-up-comedy-specials-966401|title=Amazon Inks Groundbreaking Deal for 14 Indian Stand-Up Comedy Specials|last=Bhushan|first=Nyay|date=20 January 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> He performs primarily in English, switching to [[Hindi]] for comic effect.\n\n==Personal life==\nKenny Sebastian was born on 31 December 1990 in [[Pala, Kerala|Pala]], [[Kerala]], India in a [[Catholic]] [[Malayali]] family and was brought up in [[Bangalore]]. His father was in the [[Navy]], hence Kenny migrated throughout his childhood. He posted a YouTube video introducing his father to superhero characters.A fun fact about him is that he is colour blind, not many people are aware of it. He speaks English, [[Malayalam]] (mother-tongue) and [[Hindi]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/carry-on-kenny-sebastian-in-conversation-with-the-die-trying-comedian/article22836378.ece|title=Carry on, Kenny Sebastian: In conversation with the 'Die Trying' comedian|first=Susanna Myrtle|last=Lazarus|date=23 February 2018|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> He also has his own [[production house]] named SuperHuman Studioz. <ref>{{Citation|title=Chai Time Comedy with Kenny Sebastian : Being a Color Blind Painter.|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P8wjHyhDs38|language=en|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref> Kenny is also an undergraduate in painting. <ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cdsnc70Un14 |title=Exams, CBSE, Punishments - Stand Up Comedy by Kenny Sebastian |work=Kenny Sebastian |publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=28 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKenny made songs from tweets, popularly known as ''#KennySing4Me''. This gained him his initial popularity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/shayanroy/kenny-sing-4-me|title= KennySing4Me }}</ref> He also created an improvised sketch show for [[Comedy Central]] known as ''The Living Room''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afaqs.com/news/media/42539_comedy-central-to-premiere-the-living-room|title=Comedy Central to premiere 'The Living Room'|website=afaqs!|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> He co-wrote and acted in the [[web series]] called ''Star Boyz''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eventseeker.com/artist/76831-kenny-sebastian|title=Kenny Sebastian - Artist Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=eventseeker.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> He did a [[cameo appearance|cameo]] in the web series ''Humorously Yours'', in ''Better Life Foundation'' by Naveen Richard and in ''Pushpavalli'' by [[Sumukhi Suresh]]. He also has an original series ''Die Trying'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/web-series/kenny-sebastian-die-trying-amazon-prime-5066515|title=  Die Trying actor Kenny Sebastian: It's painful to create music, stand-up is easier|date=17 February 2018}}</ref> an improvised show ''The Improvisers: Something From Nothing'' along with [[Abish Mathew]], [[Kanan Gill]] and [[Kaneez Surka]] and a [[sketch comedy]] show ''Sketchy Behaviour'' co-written and co-starring [[Kanan Gill]] on [[Amazon Prime Video]].He also started his mini series named \"Getting there\" which has 3 episodes. \n\nHe is a [[judge]] for ''[[Comicstaan]]'', a comedy hunt [[reality show]] on [[Amazon Prime Video]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/hindi/2018/jul/04/comicstaan-top-comics-kanan-gill-kenny-sebastian-sumukhi-suresh-others-to-redefine-future-of-f-1837776.html|title='Comicstaan': Top comics Kanan Gill, Kenny Sebastian, Sumukhi Suresh, others to redefine future of funny|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nHe brings out videos from his standup routines and the occasional ''Chai Time With Kenny'' on his [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/entertainment-news/bollywood-news/kenny-sebastian-a-stand-up-comedian-filmmaker-and-an-all-rounder|title=Kenny Sebastian: A stand-up comedian, filmmaker, and an all rounder|last=World|first=Republic|website=Republic World|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Platform !! Name !! Notes \n|-\n| 2014 || rowspan=\"8\"| [[YouTube]] || Journey to the Center of My Brain || Himself\n|-\n| 2015 || Insides Out || Himself\n|-\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2016\n|Star Boyz <ref>{{Citation|last=Kenny Sebastian|title=3 South Indian Boys in Space {{!}} STAR BOYZ {{!}} CHAATS Ep 1 #LaughterGames|date=5 May 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p56_5T7oiFY|access-date=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n|Actor\n|-\n|A Door through a Window\n|Himself\n|-\n|Breezer Vivid\n|Alongside [[Abish Mathew]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2017-2018 || rowspan=2| Son Of Abish \n| Season 2 with [[Radhika Apte]]\n|-\n| Season 4 with [[Yami Gautam]]\n|-\n|2017\u2013Present\n|Chai Time with Kenny\n|Himself\n|- \n|rowspan=2| 2017 || rowspan=2 |''[[Amazon Video]]''|| Don't Make That Face by Naveen Richard || [[Film director|Director]]\n|-\n| Don't Be That Guy<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/kenny-sebastian-dont-be-that-guy/article18188320.ece|title=Kenny Sebastian: Don't Be That Guy}}</ref>|| Himself \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2018\n| rowspan=\"3\" |''[[Amazon Video]]''\n| Die Trying ||Kenny <ref>{{cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/web-series/die-trying-kenny-sebastian-amazon-prime-review-5068017|title=Die Trying review: This Kenny Sebastian 'Brohemian Rhapsody' is enjoyable in parts|date=18 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/tv/die-trying-review-kenny-sebastian-s-amazon-show-is-a-middle-finger-to-middle-class-indian-establishment/story-9GrJ4QU6kX9PWViYdoEJdL.html|title=Die Trying review: Kenny Sebastian's Amazon show is a middle finger to middle-class Indian establishment|date=14 February 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|The Improvisers: Something From Nothing\n|Alongside [[Kanan Gill]], [[Abish Mathew]], [[Kaneez Surka]]\n|-\n|[[Comicstaan]]\n|Himself- Judge\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2019\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''[[Amazon Video]]''\n|Sketchy Behaviour|||Alongside [[Kanan Gill]]\n|-\n|[[Comicstaan | Comicstaan: Season 2]]\n|Himself- Judge\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|4131562}}\n*https://www.youtube.com/user/kennethseb on YouTube\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sebastian, Kenny}}\n[[Category:Indian stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Indian Internet celebrities]]\n[[Category:Indian YouTubers]]\n", "name_user": "103.70.198.72", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenny_Sebastian"}
{"title_page": "New Yorker Staats-Zeitung", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                 = New Yorker Staats-Zeitung\n| school               = \n| logo                 = \n| logo_size            = \n| logo_alt             = \n| image                = New Yorker Staats Zeitung Building 1876.png\n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = Staats-Zeitung Building (1873\u20131907),<br> [[Park Row (Manhattan)|Printing House Square]], New York City\n| motto                = \n| type                 = Weekly newspaper\n| format               = \n| owner                = Jes Rau\n| founder              = <!-- or |founders= -->\n| publisher            = \n| president            = \n| editor               = \n| staff                = \n| foundation           = 1834\n| political            = \n| language             = German\n| ceased publication   = \n| relaunched           = \n| headquarters         = [[Sarasota, Florida]]\n| circulation          = \n| circulation_date     = \n| circulation_ref      = \n| readership           = \n| sister newspapers    = \n| ISSN                 = 1542-1465\n| oclc                 = \n| RNI                  = \n| website              = http://www.germancorner.com/NYStaatsZ/\n| free                 = \n| dirinteractive       = \n| publishing_country   = \n| publishing_city      = \n}}\n\nThe '''''New Yorker Staats-Zeitung''''', nicknamed '''''\"The Staats\"''''', claims to be the leading [[German language|German-language]] weekly [[newspaper]] in the [[United States]]<ref>For example, on the [http://www.germancorner.com/NYStaatsZ/ ''Staats-Zeitung'' website].</ref> and is one of the oldest, having been published since the mid-1830s.  In the late 19th century, it was one of [[New York City]]'s major daily newspapers, exceeded in circulation only by the ''[[New York World]]'' and the ''[[New-York Tribune]]''.<ref name=\"History\">\"History of a New York City Institution\", retrieved from the ''Staats-Zeitung'' web site on April 15, 2012.  The information provided on this web page is not referenced to primary sources and sometimes conflicts in details (such as dates or spellings) with known reliable sources.</ref>  Among other achievements, as of its sesquicentennial anniversary in 1984 it had never missed a publication date, thereby laying claim to the title of being continuously published longer than any other newspaper (of any language) in America.<ref>Page B-2, ''New Yorker Staats Zeitung'', 17/18 November 1984.  Sonderbeilage Der New Yorker Staats-Zeitung Und Herold: 1834-1984. 150 Jahre New Yorker Staats-Zeitung.  (150th Anniversary Commemorative Supplement)</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n{{multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n| align     = left\n| direction = vertical\n| width     = 165\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n| image1    = Gustavus Adolphus Neumann, ca 1860.jpg\n| alt1      =\n| caption1  = [[Gustavus Adolphus Neumann]], editor 1834\u20131853\n<!-- Image 2 -->\n| image2    = Anthony Eickhoff.jpg\n| alt2      =\n| caption2  = [[Anthony Eickhoff]], editor 1854\u20131856\n<!-- Image 3 -->\n| image3    = Anna Behr Uhl Ottendorfer.jpg\n| alt3      =\n| caption3  =[[Anna Ottendorfer|Anna Uhl Ottendorfer]], business manager 1845\u20131884\n<!-- Image 4 -->\n| image4    =Oswald-Ottendorfer-cigarette-card.jpg\n| alt4      =\n| caption4  =[[Oswald Ottendorfer]], editor 1858\u20131900\n\n<!-- Image 5 -->\n| image5    = Herman Ridder (Hyphenations).jpg\n| alt5      =\n| caption5  = [[Herman Ridder]], manager 1890\u20131915\n}}\nThe ''Staats-Zeitung'' was founded in New York City in 1834 by a society of [[German-American]] businessmen.<ref name=\"Epitome\">''An Epitome of the New-Yorker Staats-Zeitung's Sixty-Five Years of Progress''.  1899.  Complimentary pamphlet prepared and distributed by the Staats-Zeitung to describe its history and new press capacity.</ref>  The partners included George Zahm, Stepan Molitor, Conrad Braeker, and [[Gustavus Adolphus Neumann|Gustav Adolph Neumann]], with Neumann serving as editor-in-chief (as well as reporter and production foreman).  Neumann subsequently purchased shares of the enterprise until, in the late 1830s, he obtained a majority, after which the society was dissolved and he became sole owner.\nThe first issue was published on December 24, 1834.  The nascent newspaper consisted of four pages and was printed weekly using a Washington hand-press.  Initial circulation was small, limited by the capacity of the press (2000 impressions per day) and by the size of the audience (primarily German immigrants).  At that time there were approximately 10,000 German-born citizens in New York City.\n\nGrowth during the first few years of the paper's existence was also impeded by the [[Panic of 1837|Financial Panic of 1837]], but by 1839 it was sufficiently successful to move to a location on Frankfort Street, a few blocks from [[New York City Hall|City Hall]]. Under Neumann's guidance, improvements to the physical plant were undertaken to support the growth that accompanied its increasing influence.  In 1843, on obtaining a single cylinder hand-operated press that could print 600 sheets per hour, he converted the ''Staats-Zeitung'' to a tri-weekly publication.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/>\n\nThe paper's staff also expanded as it grew.  Notable additions included: Jacob Uhl, who may have been hired as a printer as early as 1836;<ref name=\"History\"/> Jacob's wife [[Anna Ottendorfer|Anna Uhl]], who worked as a compositor, secretary, and business manager;<ref name=\"dab\">{{Cite DAB|title=Ottendorfer, Anna Behr Uhl|author=Edwin H. Zeydel|volume=VII, Part 2|pages=106\u2013107}}</ref> and [[Oswald Ottendorfer]], who appears to have been hired in the counting room in 1850.<ref name=\"History\"/>  All had a role to play in the unfolding story.\n\nIn 1845 Jacob Uhl bought ownership and publishing rights from Neumann who, nonetheless, continued in an editorial capacity until 1853. Working together, Jacob and Anna Uhl increased both advertising patronage and circulation, enabling a shift to daily publication not long after the purchase.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/>  Subsequently, the paper's physical plant was moved to and combined with a printing office owned by Jacob Uhl, and a Sunday edition was added on January 3, 1848.  The enhanced paper quickly outgrew both the press capabilities and the physical space of the printing office, and in 1850 Uhl purchased property specifically to house the ''Staats-Zeitung''.  He installed the most rapid printing presses then available in a new building erected on the property for that purpose.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/>   \n[[File:New Yorker Staats Zeitung Building 1858.jpg|thumb|upright|Staats-Zeitung Building, 1857\u20131873]]\nWhen Jacob Uhl died in 1852, Anna Uhl took over management of the newspaper.  The paper continued to thrive, and by 1857 another expansion was required.  Anna Uhl purchased property on what was then [[Park Row (Manhattan)|Chatham Street]] (also known at that time as \"Newspaper Row\", now Park Row) and had a suitable building erected. One of the first rotary type-revolving presses was installed, increasing the publishing capacity to 4,000 papers per hour.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/>\n\nIn 1858, Anna Uhl appointed Oswald Ottendorfer \u2013 who had gradually been contributing more assistance \u2013 as editor.  In 1859 Anna Uhl and Oswald Ottendorfer were married, and continued to operate the paper together, with Oswald serving as editor and publisher while Anna functioned as business manager.  In 1873 another expansion was completed under the German-American architect [[J. William Schickel]] at 17 Chatham Street (pictured below). Anna Ottendorfer continued as business manager until shortly before her death in 1884 when her son Edward Uhl<ref>A short biography of Edward Uhl is available in German at: [[:de:Edward Uhl]]</ref> succeeded her. Together Anna and Oswald Ottendorfer developed the ''Staats-Zeitung'' into a major newspaper. By the 1870s, its circulation was comparable to [[English language|English-language]] newspapers like the ''[[New York Tribune]]'' and the ''[[New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"anb\">{{Cite ANB|title=Ottendorfer, Anna Behr Uhl|volume=16|pages=841\u2013842|author=James M. Bergquist |id=1601241}}</ref>\n\nIn 1879, the property of the paper was changed into a stock company.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/famousgiversand00boltgoog|page=[https://archive.org/details/famousgiversand00boltgoog/page/n377 329]|title=Famous givers and their gifts|publisher=T.Y. Crowell|author=Sarah Knowles Bolton|year=1896}}</ref> When Oswald Ottendorfer died in 1900, the newspaper was sold to [[Herman Ridder]], who had become manager and trustee in 1890.<ref>{{Cite Collier's|wstitle=Ridder, Herman}}</ref> Ridder went on to contribute to the foundation of the [[Knight Ridder]] conglomerate, and the ''Staats-Zeitung'' gradually became a side line. It stayed in the Ridder family until 1953, when it was sold to the Steuer family who changed from a daily newspaper to three times a week and finally a weekly. In 1989, it was sold to Jes Rau.\n\nFrom 1968 to 1969, the German entertainer and comedian [[Herbert Feuerstein]] was editor-in-chief of the newspaper.\n\n==Political influence==\n[[File:Enemy Activities - Miscellaneous - German-Americans grouped around the bulletin board of the Staats-zeitung, New York at the outbreak of the war. 1914 - NARA - 31480226 (cropped).jpg|thumb|German Americans outside the ''Staats-Zeitung'' offices, reading about the outbreak of World War I (1914)]]\nThe German-American businessmen who founded the ''New Yorker Staats-Zeitung'' in 1834 did so with a specific agenda in mind.  The paper was to be the voice of German-Americans who opposed the [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig Party]], then the dominant political force in New York City.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/> This stance aligned the paper with the objectives of the [[Jacksonian Democrats]], who were at that time developing the [[Tammany Hall]] political machine.  Mr. Neumann's editorials took forceful and animated positions in support of the interests of German-American immigrants who sought to become full participants in the governance of their new home.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/>\n\nHowever, the paper was also concerned with events in Europe, undoubtedly because German immigration at this time was often motivated by political repression in Germany.  Jacob Uhl, for example, is said to have left Germany a year or two after being jailed for participating in a democratic riot in [[Frankfurt]].<ref name=\"History\"/>  As owner of the paper, he supported the [[Revolutions of 1848 in the German states|German Revolution of 1848]]. Oswald Ottendorfer was an active participant in those European uprisings \u2013 in 1848 in [[Vienna]] and in 1849 in [[Saxony]].  His passion for things political remained after he immigrated to America, and he continued to develop the political clout of the ''Staats-Zeitung'' after he became editor in 1858.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/>\n\nFrom 1860 to 1864, [[Franz Umbscheiden]] \u2013 who also participated in the German Revolution of 1848 \u2013 was on the staff.<ref>{{Cite book| author=Carl Wittke| title=Refugees of Revolution: The German Forty-Eighters in America| publisher=[[University of Pennsylvania Press]]| year=1952| location=Philadelphia| page=270| url=https://archive.org/details/refugeesofrevolu008276mbp}}</ref>\n[[File:Staatszeitung und Herold NY 1944.jpg|thumb|Front page of the ''New Yorker Staats-Zeitung und Herold''<br>(May 3, 1944)]]\nLeading up to [[World War II]], the paper had an evolving view of [[Adolf Hitler]] and the [[Third Reich]]. In 1934, the Staats-Zeitung opposed the \"mock trial\" of Hitler to be held at [[Madison Square Garden]], calling [[Nazi]] Germany a \"friendly nation\" and asking the U.S. to respect \"the laws and deeds of the statutory regime of the German Reich; the laws and deeds of the lawful administration of government of a friendly power\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Expect Crowded Courtroom at Hitler \u2018trial\u2019 Tomorrow|url=http://www.jta.org/1934/03/06/archive/expect-crowded-courtroom-at-hitler-trial-tomorrow|accessdate=8 October 2015|agency=JTA|date=March 6, 1934}}</ref> A year earlier, however, the paper published an editorial, entitled \"Blind Fanaticism\" and signed by its then editor, Benjamin F. Ridder, denouncing the Nazi persecution of Jews.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beck|first1=Alfred M.|title=Hitler\u2019s Ambivalent Attach\u00e9|publisher=Potomac Books|page=327}}</ref> Later, the paper revealed a strongly anti-Nazi position, publishing many anti-Nazi editorials and articles, despite Friends of New Germany leader [[Heinz Spankn\u00f6bel]]\u2019s attempt to storm the paper's office and force the editors to write Nazi-sympathetic articles. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newyorkhistoryreviewarticles.blogspot.com/2016/03/|title=\u201cHitlerism Invades America\u201d Supporters of Hitler in New York City and the Nazi Threat in America, 1930-1934|date=March 21, 2016}}</ref>\n{{clearleft}}\n==See also==\n* ''[[Anzeiger des Westens]]'', the German-language daily paper in [[St. Louis]] founded one year later, that became the largest newspaper of any language in the state\n* [[Carl Eytel]], an early 20th-century German-American artist living in [[Palm Springs, California]], who contributed to the newspaper over a 14-year period<ref>{{cite news| last=Law| first=George| title=Desert Painter: Carl Eytel| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| location=Los Angeles, CA| date=January 28, 1923| page=X17 (Illustrated Magazine)| ISSN= 0458-3035| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/328898372.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jan+28%2C+1923&author=GEORGE+LAW&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(1923-Current+File)&edition=&startpage=XI7&desc=Carl+Eytel+DESERT+PAINTER| quote=...in a role of raconteur unbeknown to his friends, [he] was regularly contributing illustrated articles...telling the York State Germans and the subscribers in all parts of the world about his long journeys and adventures....}} {{Subscription required}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite Appletons'|wstitle=Ottendorfer, Oswald|year=1900}}\n* Karl J. R. Arndt and May E. Olson, ''The German Language Press of the Americas'', Volume I: \"History and Bibliography, 1732 to 1955\", 3rd revised edition, 1976.\n* Carl Wittke, ''The German Language Press in America'', 1957.\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9E06E2D81238E033A25751C0A9629C94659FD7CF Obituary of Anna Ottendorfer] at ''[[The New York Times]]''.  This source disagrees with the Zeydel and Bergquist biographies on Anna Ottendorfer's maiden name and when she and Jacob Uhl arrived in America.\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.germancorner.com/NYStaatsZ/}}\n* [http://www.germancorner.com/NYStaatsZ/history.html History of a New York City institution] (at the ''Staats-Zeitung'' website)\n* [http://www.historische-zeitungen.de/New-Yorker-Staats-Zeitung.php Historical Newspapers, Germany]\n\n{{Ethnicity in New York City}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Newspapers published in New York City]]\n[[Category:German-American culture]]\n[[Category:Weekly newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1834]]\n[[Category:German-American history]]\n[[Category:German-American culture in New York City]]\n[[Category:1834 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:German-language newspapers published in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                 = New Yorker Staats-Zeitung\n| school               = \n| logo                 = \n| logo_size            = \n| logo_alt             = \n| image                = File:New Yorker Staats Zeitung Building 1876.png\n| image_size           = 280px\n\n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = Staats-Zeitung Building (1873\u20131907),<br> [[Park Row (Manhattan)|Printing House Square]], New York City\n| motto                = \n| type                 = Weekly newspaper\n| format               = \n| owner                = Jes Rau\n| founder              = <!-- or |founders= -->\n| publisher            = \n| president            = \n| editor               = \n| staff                = \n| foundation           = 1834\n| political            = \n| language             = German\n| ceased publication   = \n| relaunched           = \n| headquarters         = [[Sarasota, Florida]]\n| circulation          = \n| circulation_date     = \n| circulation_ref      = \n| readership           = \n| sister newspapers    = \n| ISSN                 = 1542-1465\n| oclc                 = \n| RNI                  = \n| website              = http://www.germancorner.com/NYStaatsZ/\n| free                 = \n| dirinteractive       = \n| publishing_country   = \n| publishing_city      = \n}}\n\nThe '''''New Yorker Staats-Zeitung''''', nicknamed '''''\"The Staats\"''''', claims to be the leading [[German language|German-language]] weekly [[newspaper]] in the [[United States]]<ref>For example, on the [http://www.germancorner.com/NYStaatsZ/ ''Staats-Zeitung'' website].</ref> and is one of the oldest, having been published since the mid-1830s.  In the late 19th century, it was one of [[New York City]]'s major daily newspapers, exceeded in circulation only by the ''[[New York World]]'' and the ''[[New-York Tribune]]''.<ref name=\"History\">\"History of a New York City Institution\", retrieved from the ''Staats-Zeitung'' web site on April 15, 2012.  The information provided on this web page is not referenced to primary sources and sometimes conflicts in details (such as dates or spellings) with known reliable sources.</ref>  Among other achievements, as of its sesquicentennial anniversary in 1984 it had never missed a publication date, thereby laying claim to the title of being continuously published longer than any other newspaper (of any language) in America.<ref>Page B-2, ''New Yorker Staats Zeitung'', 17/18 November 1984.  Sonderbeilage Der New Yorker Staats-Zeitung Und Herold: 1834-1984. 150 Jahre New Yorker Staats-Zeitung.  (150th Anniversary Commemorative Supplement)</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n{{multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n| align     = left\n| direction = vertical\n| width     = 165\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n| image1    = Gustavus Adolphus Neumann, ca 1860.jpg\n| alt1      =\n| caption1  = [[Gustavus Adolphus Neumann]], editor 1834\u20131853\n<!-- Image 2 -->\n| image2    = Anthony Eickhoff.jpg\n| alt2      =\n| caption2  = [[Anthony Eickhoff]], editor 1854\u20131856\n<!-- Image 3 -->\n| image3    = Anna Behr Uhl Ottendorfer.jpg\n| alt3      =\n| caption3  =[[Anna Ottendorfer|Anna Uhl Ottendorfer]], business manager 1845\u20131884\n<!-- Image 4 -->\n| image4    =Oswald-Ottendorfer-cigarette-card.jpg\n| alt4      =\n| caption4  =[[Oswald Ottendorfer]], editor 1858\u20131900\n\n<!-- Image 5 -->\n| image5    = Herman Ridder (Hyphenations).jpg\n| alt5      =\n| caption5  = [[Herman Ridder]], manager 1890\u20131915\n}}\nThe ''Staats-Zeitung'' was founded in New York City in 1834 by a society of [[German-American]] businessmen.<ref name=\"Epitome\">''An Epitome of the New-Yorker Staats-Zeitung's Sixty-Five Years of Progress''.  1899.  Complimentary pamphlet prepared and distributed by the Staats-Zeitung to describe its history and new press capacity.</ref>  The partners included George Zahm, Stepan Molitor, Conrad Braeker, and [[Gustavus Adolphus Neumann|Gustav Adolph Neumann]], with Neumann serving as editor-in-chief (as well as reporter and production foreman).  Neumann subsequently purchased shares of the enterprise until, in the late 1830s, he obtained a majority, after which the society was dissolved and he became sole owner.\nThe first issue was published on December 24, 1834.  The nascent newspaper consisted of four pages and was printed weekly using a Washington hand-press.  Initial circulation was small, limited by the capacity of the press (2000 impressions per day) and by the size of the audience (primarily German immigrants).  At that time there were approximately 10,000 German-born citizens in New York City.\n\nGrowth during the first few years of the paper's existence was also impeded by the [[Panic of 1837|Financial Panic of 1837]], but by 1839 it was sufficiently successful to move to a location on Frankfort Street, a few blocks from [[New York City Hall|City Hall]]. Under Neumann's guidance, improvements to the physical plant were undertaken to support the growth that accompanied its increasing influence.  In 1843, on obtaining a single cylinder hand-operated press that could print 600 sheets per hour, he converted the ''Staats-Zeitung'' to a tri-weekly publication.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/>\n\nThe paper's staff also expanded as it grew.  Notable additions included: Jacob Uhl, who may have been hired as a printer as early as 1836;<ref name=\"History\"/> Jacob's wife [[Anna Ottendorfer|Anna Uhl]], who worked as a compositor, secretary, and business manager;<ref name=\"dab\">{{Cite DAB|title=Ottendorfer, Anna Behr Uhl|author=Edwin H. Zeydel|volume=VII, Part 2|pages=106\u2013107}}</ref> and [[Oswald Ottendorfer]], who appears to have been hired in the counting room in 1850.<ref name=\"History\"/>  All had a role to play in the unfolding story.\n\nIn 1845 Jacob Uhl bought ownership and publishing rights from Neumann who, nonetheless, continued in an editorial capacity until 1853. Working together, Jacob and Anna Uhl increased both advertising patronage and circulation, enabling a shift to daily publication not long after the purchase.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/>  Subsequently, the paper's physical plant was moved to and combined with a printing office owned by Jacob Uhl, and a Sunday edition was added on January 3, 1848.  The enhanced paper quickly outgrew both the press capabilities and the physical space of the printing office, and in 1850 Uhl purchased property specifically to house the ''Staats-Zeitung''.  He installed the most rapid printing presses then available in a new building erected on the property for that purpose.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/>   \n[[File:New Yorker Staats Zeitung Building 1858.jpg|thumb|upright|Staats-Zeitung Building, 1857\u20131873]]\nWhen Jacob Uhl died in 1852, Anna Uhl took over management of the newspaper.  The paper continued to thrive, and by 1857 another expansion was required.  Anna Uhl purchased property on what was then [[Park Row (Manhattan)|Chatham Street]] (also known at that time as \"Newspaper Row\", now Park Row) and had a suitable building erected. One of the first rotary type-revolving presses was installed, increasing the publishing capacity to 4,000 papers per hour.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/>\n\nIn 1858, Anna Uhl appointed Oswald Ottendorfer \u2013 who had gradually been contributing more assistance \u2013 as editor.  In 1859 Anna Uhl and Oswald Ottendorfer were married, and continued to operate the paper together, with Oswald serving as editor and publisher while Anna functioned as business manager.  In 1873 another expansion was completed under the German-American architect [[J. William Schickel]] at 17 Chatham Street (pictured below). Anna Ottendorfer continued as business manager until shortly before her death in 1884 when her son Edward Uhl<ref>A short biography of Edward Uhl is available in German at: [[:de:Edward Uhl]]</ref> succeeded her. Together Anna and Oswald Ottendorfer developed the ''Staats-Zeitung'' into a major newspaper. By the 1870s, its circulation was comparable to [[English language|English-language]] newspapers like the ''[[New York Tribune]]'' and the ''[[New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"anb\">{{Cite ANB|title=Ottendorfer, Anna Behr Uhl|volume=16|pages=841\u2013842|author=James M. Bergquist |id=1601241}}</ref>\n\nIn 1879, the property of the paper was changed into a stock company.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/famousgiversand00boltgoog|page=[https://archive.org/details/famousgiversand00boltgoog/page/n377 329]|title=Famous givers and their gifts|publisher=T.Y. Crowell|author=Sarah Knowles Bolton|year=1896}}</ref> When Oswald Ottendorfer died in 1900, the newspaper was sold to [[Herman Ridder]], who had become manager and trustee in 1890.<ref>{{Cite Collier's|wstitle=Ridder, Herman}}</ref> Ridder went on to contribute to the foundation of the [[Knight Ridder]] conglomerate, and the ''Staats-Zeitung'' gradually became a side line. It stayed in the Ridder family until 1953, when it was sold to the Steuer family who changed from a daily newspaper to three times a week and finally a weekly. In 1989, it was sold to Jes Rau.\n\nFrom 1968 to 1969, the German entertainer and comedian [[Herbert Feuerstein]] was editor-in-chief of the newspaper.\n\n==Political influence==\n[[File:Enemy Activities - Miscellaneous - German-Americans grouped around the bulletin board of the Staats-zeitung, New York at the outbreak of the war. 1914 - NARA - 31480226 (cropped).jpg|thumb|German Americans outside the ''Staats-Zeitung'' offices, reading about the outbreak of World War I (1914)]]\nThe German-American businessmen who founded the ''New Yorker Staats-Zeitung'' in 1834 did so with a specific agenda in mind.  The paper was to be the voice of German-Americans who opposed the [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig Party]], then the dominant political force in New York City.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/> This stance aligned the paper with the objectives of the [[Jacksonian Democrats]], who were at that time developing the [[Tammany Hall]] political machine.  Mr. Neumann's editorials took forceful and animated positions in support of the interests of German-American immigrants who sought to become full participants in the governance of their new home.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/>\n\nHowever, the paper was also concerned with events in Europe, undoubtedly because German immigration at this time was often motivated by political repression in Germany.  Jacob Uhl, for example, is said to have left Germany a year or two after being jailed for participating in a democratic riot in [[Frankfurt]].<ref name=\"History\"/>  As owner of the paper, he supported the [[Revolutions of 1848 in the German states|German Revolution of 1848]]. Oswald Ottendorfer was an active participant in those European uprisings \u2013 in 1848 in [[Vienna]] and in 1849 in [[Saxony]].  His passion for things political remained after he immigrated to America, and he continued to develop the political clout of the ''Staats-Zeitung'' after he became editor in 1858.<ref name=\"Epitome\"/>\n\nFrom 1860 to 1864, [[Franz Umbscheiden]] \u2013 who also participated in the German Revolution of 1848 \u2013 was on the staff.<ref>{{Cite book| author=Carl Wittke| title=Refugees of Revolution: The German Forty-Eighters in America| publisher=[[University of Pennsylvania Press]]| year=1952| location=Philadelphia| page=270| url=https://archive.org/details/refugeesofrevolu008276mbp}}</ref>\n[[File:Staatszeitung und Herold NY 1944.jpg|thumb|Front page of the ''New Yorker Staats-Zeitung und Herold'' (May 3, 1944)]]\nLeading up to [[World War II]], the paper had an evolving view of [[Adolf Hitler]] and the [[Third Reich]]. In 1934, the Staats-Zeitung opposed the \"mock trial\" of Hitler to be held at [[Madison Square Garden]], calling [[Nazi]] Germany a \"friendly nation\" and asking the U.S. to respect \"the laws and deeds of the statutory regime of the German Reich; the laws and deeds of the lawful administration of government of a friendly power\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Expect Crowded Courtroom at Hitler \u2018trial\u2019 Tomorrow|url=http://www.jta.org/1934/03/06/archive/expect-crowded-courtroom-at-hitler-trial-tomorrow|accessdate=8 October 2015|agency=JTA|date=March 6, 1934}}</ref> A year earlier, however, the paper published an editorial, entitled \"Blind Fanaticism\" and signed by its then editor, Benjamin F. Ridder, denouncing the Nazi persecution of Jews.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beck|first1=Alfred M.|title=Hitler\u2019s Ambivalent Attach\u00e9|publisher=Potomac Books|page=327}}</ref> Later, the paper revealed a strongly anti-Nazi position, publishing many anti-Nazi editorials and articles, despite Friends of New Germany leader [[Heinz Spankn\u00f6bel]]\u2019s attempt to storm the paper's office and force the editors to write Nazi-sympathetic articles. <ref> https://newyorkhistoryreviewarticles.blogspot.com/2016/03/?m=0 </ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Anzeiger des Westens]]'', the German-language daily paper in [[St. Louis]] founded one year later, that became the largest newspaper of any language in the state\n* [[Carl Eytel]], an early 20th-century German-American artist living in [[Palm Springs, California]], who contributed to the newspaper over a 14-year period<ref>{{cite news| last=Law| first=George| title=Desert Painter: Carl Eytel| newspaper=Los Angeles Times| location=Los Angeles, CA| date=January 28, 1923| page=X17 (Illustrated Magazine)| ISSN= 0458-3035| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/328898372.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jan+28%2C+1923&author=GEORGE+LAW&pub=Los+Angeles+Times+(1923-Current+File)&edition=&startpage=XI7&desc=Carl+Eytel+DESERT+PAINTER| quote=...in a role of raconteur unbeknown to his friends, [he] was regularly contributing illustrated articles...telling the York State Germans and the subscribers in all parts of the world about his long journeys and adventures....}} {{Subscription required}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite Appletons'|wstitle=Ottendorfer, Oswald|year=1900}}\n* Karl J. R. Arndt and May E. Olson, ''The German Language Press of the Americas'', Volume I: \"History and Bibliography, 1732 to 1955\", 3rd revised edition, 1976.\n* Carl Wittke, ''The German Language Press in America'', 1957.\n* [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9E06E2D81238E033A25751C0A9629C94659FD7CF Obituary of Anna Ottendorfer] at ''[[The New York Times]]''.  This source disagrees with the Zeydel and Bergquist biographies on Anna Ottendorfer's maiden name and when she and Jacob Uhl arrived in America.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.germancorner.com/NYStaatsZ/}}\n* [http://www.germancorner.com/NYStaatsZ/history.html History of a New York City institution] (at the ''Staats-Zeitung'' website)\n* [http://www.historische-zeitungen.de/New-Yorker-Staats-Zeitung.php Historical Newspapers, Germany]\n\n{{Ethnicity in New York City}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Newspapers published in New York City]]\n[[Category:German-American culture]]\n[[Category:Weekly newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1834]]\n[[Category:German-American history]]\n[[Category:German-American culture in New York City]]\n[[Category:1834 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:German-language newspapers published in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Lotje", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 1 bare reference(s) with reFill 2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Yorker_Staats-Zeitung"}
{"title_page": "Sierentz station", "text_new": "{{Infobox station\n| name = Sierentz {{rail-interchange|fr|rail}}\n| type = Train\n| image = File:Gare de Sierentz.jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_caption = Sierentz station\n| address = Rue de Lattre de Tassigny, 68510 Sierentz\n| coordinates = {{coord|47.655686|7.45874|type:railwaystation_region:FR|display=inline,title}}\n| line = [[Strasbourg\u2013Basel railway]]\n| other = \n| structure = \n| platform = \n| depth = \n| levels = \n| tracks = \n| parking = \n| bicycle = \n| baggage_check = \n| opened = \n| closed = \n| rebuilt = \n| electrified = \n| ADA = \n| code = \n| owned = [[R\u00e9seau Ferr\u00e9 de France|RFF]] / [[SNCF]]\n| zone = \n| former = \n| passengers = \n| pass_year = \n| pass_percent = \n| pass_system = \n| mpassengers = \n| services = {{s-rail|title=SNCF}}\n{{s-line|system=TER Grand Est|line=A15|previous=Habsheim|next=Bartenheim}}\n| map_locator = \n}}\nThe '''Gare de Sierentz''' is a [[railway station]] serving the [[commuter town]] of [[Sierentz]], [[Alsace]], France, located between [[Mulhouse]] and [[Basel]].\n\n\n\nOpened in 1840 by the [[Compagnie du chemin de fer de Strasbourg \u00e0 B\u00e2le]], the railway station is a stop on the SNCF national network. The station is currently served by [[TER Grand Est]] trains between [[Mulhouse station|Mulhouse]] and [[Basel SBB railway station|Basel SBB]]. \n \n== History ==\n[[File:Gare-Sierentz-1920.jpg|thumb|Gare de Sierentz in 1920. ]]\n<br />\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111007110959/http://www.ter-sncf.com/regions/alsace/fr/se_deplacer_en_ter/avant_mon_voyage/fiches_horaires/default.aspx Timetables TER Alsace] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sierentz}}\n[[Category:Railway stations in Haut-Rhin]]\n\n{{Alsace-railstation-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox station\n | name= Gare de Sierentz {{rail-interchange|fr|rail}}\n | type= Train\n | image=File:Gare de Sierentz.jpg\n | image_size=\n | image_caption=Sierentz station\n | address= Rue de Lattre de Tassigny, 68510 Sierentz\n | coordinates= {{coord|47.655686|7.45874|type:railwaystation_region:FR|display=inline,title}}\n | line=[[Strasbourg\u2013Basel railway]]\n | other=\n | structure=\n | platform=\n | depth=\n | levels=\n | tracks=\n | parking=\n | bicycle=\n | baggage_check=\n | opened=\n | closed=\n | rebuilt= \n | electrified=\n | ADA=\n | code=\n | owned= [[R\u00e9seau Ferr\u00e9 de France|RFF]] / [[SNCF]]\n | zone=\n | former=\n | passengers=\n | pass_year=\n | pass_percent=\n | pass_system=\n | mpassengers=\n | services={{s-rail|title=SNCF}}\n{{s-line|system=TER Grand Est|line=A15|previous=Habsheim|next=Bartenheim}}\n | map_locator=\n}}\n'''Sierentz''' is a [[railway station]] serving the [[commuter town]] of [[Sierentz]], [[Alsace]], France, located between [[Mulhouse]] and [[Basel]].\n\n\n\nOpened in 1840 by the [[Compagnie du chemin de fer de Strasbourg \u00e0 B\u00e2le]], the railway station is a stop on the SNCF national network. The station is currently served by [[TER Grand Est]] trains between [[Mulhouse station|Mulhouse]] and [[Basel SBB railway station|Basel SBB]]. \n \n== History ==\n[[File:Gare-Sierentz-1920.jpg|thumb|Gare de Sierentz in 1920. ]]\n<br />\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111007110959/http://www.ter-sncf.com/regions/alsace/fr/se_deplacer_en_ter/avant_mon_voyage/fiches_horaires/default.aspx Timetables TER Alsace] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sierentz}}\n[[Category:Railway stations in Haut-Rhin]]\n\n{{Alsace-railstation-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Epluribusunumyall", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sierentz_station"}
{"title_page": "Dixie Browning", "text_new": "{{Short description|American artist and writer}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image =  \n| name = Dixie Burrus Browning\n| caption =\n| pseudonym = Zoe Dozier,<br>Dixie Browning,<br>Bronwyn Williams (with her sister [[Mary Burrus Williams]])\n| birth_name = Dixie Burrus\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1930|9|9|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[North Carolina]], United States\n| dieth_date =\n| dieth_place =\n| children = 1\n| spouse = Mr. Browning\n| occupation = [[Novelist]], [[illustrator]]\n| nationality = American\n| period = 1976&ndash;present\n| genre = [[Romance novel|Romance]]\n| parents = [[Dick Burrus]] (father)\n| relatives = [[Mary Burrus Williams]] (sister)\n| movement =\n| notableworks =\n| influences =\n| influenced =\n| awards = [[RITA Award]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.dixiebrowning.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Dixie Browning''', n\u00e9e '''Burrus''' (born September 9, 1930 in [[North Carolina]]) is an American [[artist]] and [[writer]] of over 100 [[romance novels]]. She also has published under the pen name '''Zoe Dozier''', and with her sister [[Mary Burrus Williams]], she writes [[historical romance]] under the name '''Bronwyn Williams'''. She is a recipient of the [[RITA Award]].\n\n==Biography==\nDixie Burrus was born in 1930 on North Carolina's [[Outer Banks]], daughter of professional baseball played [[Dick Burrus|Maurice Lennon \"Dick\" Burrus]]. She learned from a young age to enjoy the water and the outdoors, and to spend plenty of time lying down with a good book as well. Browning considers herself foremost an artist. She studied and later taught art. She paints landscapes and seascapes in watercolor, and is listed in ''[[Who's Who in American Art]]''.<ref>Browne PCL</ref>\n\nIn 1975, Browning began writing a newspaper column on art. Shortly thereafter, she decided to try fiction. As she had recently begun reading romance novels, she attempted to recreate the pieces of the genre that appealed to her. This tactic worked, as in 1976, Avalon published her first two romances. She has since published over 100 category romance novels. She has been awarded a [[Romance Writers of America]] RITA Award, and been a five-time RITA finalist. She has also won three Maggies, and numerous awards from the [[National Federation of Press Women]] and the [[NC Press Club]]. At the end of 2004, after Browning had submitted yet another manuscript, she realized that writing was not as exciting for her as it had been. She began painting again, and now concentrates primarily on her art.\n\nBrowning cofounded and served as the first president of The Watercolor Society of North Carolina. She is also a co-owner of Browning Artworks in [[Frisco, North Carolina]], which features her own work as well as that of her son and daughter-in-law.\n\nBrowning lives in [[North Carolina]] with her husband of over fifty years.\n\n==Awards==\n\n===As Dixie Browning===\n* ''Renegade Player'': 1983 Rita Awards Best Novel winner\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===As Zoe Dozier===\n\n====Single Novels====\n* ''Home Again, My Love'' Avalon 1977\n* ''Warm Side of the Island'' Avalon 1977\n\n===As Dixie Browning===\n\n====Stand alone novels====\n* ''Unreasonable Summer'' Silhouette Romance 5/80\n* ''Tumbled Wall'' Silhouette Romance 10/80\n* ''Chance Tomorrow'' Silhouette Romance 1/81\n* ''Wren of Paradise'' Silhouette Romance 4/81\n* ''East of Today'' Silhouette Romance 7/81\n* ''Winter Blossom'' Silhouette Romance 11/81\n* ''Renegade Player'' Silhouette Romance 4/82\n* ''Island on the Hill'' Silhouette Romance 7/82\n* ''Logic of the Heart'' Silhouette Romance 9/82\n* ''Finders Keepers'' Silhouette Special Ed. 10/82\n* ''Loving Rescue'' Silhouette Romance 12/82\n* ''A Secret Valentine'' Silhouette Romance 2/83\n* ''Practical Dreamer'' Silhouette Special Ed. 5/83\n* ''Shadow of Yesterday'' Silhouette Desire 6/83\n* ''Reach Out to Cherish'' Silhouette Special Ed. 8/