rl=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?termGbn=month&hitYear=2017&targetTime=12&nationGbn=K|website=Gaon Music Chart|language=ko|script-title=ko:2017\ub144 12\uc6d4 Album Chart|trans-title=December 2017 Album Chart|accessdate=September 7, 2017}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/album.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=&targetTime=08&hitYear=2018&termGbn=month|website=Gaon Music Chart|language=ko|script-title=ko:2018\ub144 08\uc6d4 Album Chart|trans-title=August 2018 Album Chart|accessdate=September 6, 2018}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |79,473+\n|-\n|''Oricon'' physical sales\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |4,478+\n|-\n|''Billboard'' physical sales<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8275948/red-velvet-south-korean-kpop-group-get-to-know-10-facts|title=Red Velvet Performs in North Korea: 10 Things to Know for the Historic K-Pop Performance|date=2018-03-30|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n|3,000+\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| Region\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| Date\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| Format\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| Label\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Various<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/album/id1037732950|title=The Red \u2013 The 1st Album by Red Velvet on Apple Music|publisher=[[iTunes Store]] |accessdate=September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=2| September 9, 2015\n| [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| [[SM Entertainment]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| South Korea\n| [[Compact Disc|CD]], digital download\n| SM Entertainment, [[KT Music]]\n|}\n\n== Accolades ==\n=== Annual music awards===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:650px;\"\n|-   \n! style=\"width:50px;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:200px;\"| Award show\n! style=\"width:300px;\"| Category\n! style=\"width:200px;\"| Nominated work\n! style=\"width:50px;\"| Result\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Show Champion]] Music Awards''\n| Best Female Group Performance\n| Dumb Dumb\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2016\n| ''[[Golden Disc Awards]]''\n| Album Division Main Award\n| The Red\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| ''[[Gaon Chart Music Awards]]''\n| Song of the Month (September 2015)\n| Dumb Dumb\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n=== Music program awards ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:650px;\"\n|-   \n! style=\"width:150px;\"| Song\n! style=\"width:200px;\"| Program\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| Date\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | \"Dumb Dumb\"\n|-\n| ''[[The Show (South Korean TV series)|The Show]]'' ([[SBS MTV]])\n| September 15, 2015\n|-\n| ''[[Show Champion]]'' ([[MBC Music]])\n| September 16, 2015\n|-\n| ''[[M Countdown]]'' ([[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]])\n| September 17, 2015\n|-\n| ''[[Inkigayo]]'' ([[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]])\n| September 19, 2015\n|-\n| ''[[M Countdown]]'' ([[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]])\n| September 24, 2015\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Red Velvet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red, The}}\n[[Category:Red Velvet (group) albums]]\n[[Category:2015 albums]]\n[[Category:Korean-language albums]]\n[[Category:SM Entertainment albums]]\n[[Category:Genie Music albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Album by Red Velvet}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''The Red'' (album)}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = The Red\n| type         = Studio\n| artist       = [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]\n| cover        = The Red album by Red Velvet.jpg\n| alt          = Colorful square with red, cyan and yellow as main color, featuring five girls.\n| released     = September 9, 2015\n| recorded     = 2015\n| studio       = SM Studio Center\n| genre        = * [[K-pop|Dance-pop]]\n* [[Electro-pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Funk]]\n* [[Hip-hop]]\n| length       = 33:05\n| language     = Korean\n| label        = * [[SM Entertainment]]\n* [[Genie Music|KT Music]]\n| producer     = * [[Lee Soo-man]] ([[executive producer|exec.]])\n* [[LDN Noise]]\n* [[Ryan S. Jhun]]\n* [[Denzil Remedios|DR]]\n* [[Dsign Music]]\n* [[Kenzie (songwriter)|Kenzie]]\n* [[Deekay|Daniel Klein]]\n* [[Charli Taft]]\n* Jinbo\n* [[Dem Jointz]]\n| prev_title   = [[Ice Cream Cake (EP)|Ice Cream Cake]]\n| prev_year    = 2015\n| next_title   = [[The Velvet]]\n| next_year    = 2016\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = The Red\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Dumb Dumb (Red Velvet song)|Dumb Dumb]]\n | single1date = September 9, 2015\n}}\n{{External music video|type=studio|{{YouTube|XGdbaEDVWp0|\"Dumb Dumb\"}}}}\n}}\n'''''The Red''''' is the debut [[studio album]] by South Korean girl group [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]. It was released on September 9, 2015 by [[SM Entertainment]] and distributed by [[KT Music]], marking their second proper release in 2015 following the debut [[extended play]] [[Ice Cream Cake (EP)|''Ice Cream Cake'']] in March 2015. The album focuses solely on the group's \"Red\" image stemming from [[Red Velvet (group)#Artistry|the group's name and concept]], showing the group's vivid and bold image with mainly [[Pop music|pop]] and [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] incorporation. [[LDN Noise]], [[Ryan S. Jhun]], [[Denzil 'DR' Remedios|Denzil \"DR\" Remedios]], [[Dsign Music]], [[Kenzie (songwriter)|Kenzie]], [[Daniel \"Obi\" Klein, Charlie Taft|Deekay]], [[Charli Taft]], Jinbo, [[Dem Jointz]], as well as others, handled production of the album, with S.M. founder [[Lee Soo-man]] serving as the executive producer of the album. A similar conceptual follow-up to the album called ''[[The Velvet]]'' was later released in the first half of 2016, which was composed of mostly [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] tracks and ballads showcasing the \"Velvet\" half with a more mature and sophisticated side of the girl group.\n\nUpon its release, ''The Red'' received positive reviews from critics for its musical diversity while showing the \"quirkiness\" of Red Velvet. The album was a commercial success, becoming Red Velvet's second chart-topper on the [[Gaon Album Chart]] in South Korea. It also attained international success, becoming the group's first number one title on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' World Albums Chart for the first time, while peaking at number twenty-four on ''Billboard''{{'}}s [[Top Heatseekers|Heatseekers Albums chart]]. It was later included as ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s 10 Best K-Pop Albums of 2015.\n\nPromotion for the album was preceded by the release of the lead single \"[[Dumb Dumb]]\" on the same release day, along with live performances on weekly music shows for both \"Dumb Dumb\" and the album track \"Huff 'n' Puff\". The lead single was a commercial success, peaking at number two on the [[Gaon Digital Chart]] and number three on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard's]]'' World Digital Songs chart while becoming one of the group's signature \"Red\" singles.\n\n==Background and release==\nFollowing the group's first major release ''Ice Cream Cake'' in March 2015, S.M. Entertainment announced that Red Velvet would be returning with their first [[Studio album|full album]] in early September. On September 3, a series of image teasers were revealed on the group's official [[Instagram]] account, along with the album's tracklist. On September 4, the company announced that the full album would be released at midnight on September 9, with \"Dumb Dumb\" serving as the lead single (aka title track).<ref>{{cite web|title=Red Velvet Reveals Track List for Their First Album \"Red\" Through Fun Instagram Surprise |website=Soompi |url=http://www.soompi.com/2015/09/03/red-velvet-reveals-track-list-for-their-first-album-red-through-fun-instagram-surprise/ |accessdate=September 4, 2015 |date=September 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stoo.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?sec=enter99&idxno=2015090410011291722 |accessdate=September 4, 2015 |author=Lee So-dam |website=Sports Today |date=September 4, 2015|title=\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 9\uc6d49\uc77c \ucef4\ubc31 \ud655\uc815\u2026SM \ud558\ubc18\uae30 \uccab\uc8fc\uc790 [\uc2a4\ud3ec\uce20\ud22c\ub370\uc774]|language=Korean}}</ref> A series of video teasers was released since September 4, including song previews for \"Huff 'n' Puff\", \"Don't U Wait No More\", \"Time Slip\", \"Dumb Dumb\" and \"Red Dress\". The music video for the song was released on September 8 while the full album was released on September 9.<ref>{{cite web |title=Red Velvet to Return with Full-Length Album \u2032The Red\u2032 on September 9 |author=Lee Nancy |website=enewsWorld |url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/97625/video-red-velvet-tops-music-charts-with-dumb-dumb |accessdate=September 11, 2015 |date=September 9, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912210017/http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/97625/video-red-velvet-tops-music-charts-with-dumb-dumb |archive-date=September 12, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> There are two physical versions for the album, a \u2019\u2019Red\u2019\u2019 version and a \u2019\u2019Blue\u2019\u2019 version.\n\n==Composition==\n\n=== Concept ===\nFollowing the group's concept of promoting with both \"Red\" and \"Velvet\" images (preceded by their first EP in March 2015), ''The Red'' focuses solely on their vivid and strong \"Red\" image, while seeing the girl group embraces their \"fun, peppy\" pop-oriented side.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/6656012/red-velvet-kcon-los-angeles-2015-interview|title=Red Velvet Talk First U.S. Performance, Their New Member Yeri & Summer Songs at KCON 2015: Exclusive|date=2015-08-06|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> While talking about the album at a press conference on September 8, the members and the company also hinted at a similar conceptual promotion that will follow suit after ''The Red,'' although an S.M. Entertainment representative explained that nothing has been scheduled in particular yet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mydaily.co.kr/new_yk/html/read.php?newsid=201509081610901118&amp;ext=da|title=\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \"\uccab \uc815\uaddc\uc568\ubc94 '\ub354 \ub808\ub4dc' \ubc1c\ud45c, \ub5a8\ub9ac\uace0 \uc124\ub80c\ub2e4\" \uc18c\uac10|author=Lee Seung-rok|date=September 8, 2015|website=My Daily|language=Korean|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2015/09/08/0200000000AEN20150908008200315.html|title=Red Velvet wants to define color red for you|author=Park Sojung|date=September 8, 2015|website=Yonhap News|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> The album was later proceeded by ''[[The Red Summer (EP)|The Red Summer]]'', Red Velvet's first summer special release which portrays a brighter, more vibrant \"Red\" sound of the group.\n\n=== Songs ===\n{{Listen|filename=Dumb Dumb (song sample).ogg|title=\"Dumb Dumb\"|format=[[Ogg]]|pos=left|description=A 27-second sample of \"Dumb Dumb\", a [[pop dance]] song by Red Velvet}}The album consists of ten songs with main incorporation from [[dance-pop]] and [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]. The opening track and lead single \"[[Dumb Dumb]]\" is described as \"an [[uptempo]] dance track\" with \"infectious hook\" and \"groovy beat\". Heavily influenced by [[funk]] and [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]] elements, the song is composed by producer [[Ryan S. Jhun]] and [[British people|British]] [[production team]] [[LDN Noise]], the latter whom have previously written and produced songs for fellow [[S.M. Entertainment]] labelmate [[Shinee|SHINee]] and [[TVXQ]]. The lyrics describes a girl's awkwardness in front of the person of her affection, comparing herself to that of a mannequin.<ref>{{cite web |title=Red Velvet to Return with Full-Length Album 'The Red' on September 9 |author=Lee Ji Young |website=enewsWorld |url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/97475/red-velvet-to-return-with-full-length-album-the-red-on-september-9 |accessdate=September 4, 2015 |date=September 4, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907212759/http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/97475/red-velvet-to-return-with-full-length-album-the-red-on-september-9 |archive-date=September 7, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The rap section of \"Dumb Dumb\" includes several references to [[Michael Jackson]]'s song discography, such as  \"[[Beat It]]\", \"[[Bad (Michael Jackson song)|Bad]]\", \"[[Billie Jean]]\" and \"[[Thriller (song)|Thriller]]\". It is followed by \"Huff 'n' Puff\", an [[Electropop|electro-pop]] song that features  a [[dubstep]]-like breakdown that sings about waking up from a dream and coming back to reality, like [[Alice in Wonderland|Alice]] falling down the rabbit hole.<ref>{{Cite episode |accessdate=October 5, 2015 |series=Gayo Plaza |author=Kim Chang-ryul |network=[[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] |station=SBS Power FM |location=Seoul |date=September 24, 2015 |language=Korean}}</ref> The third track \"Campfire\" is described as an [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] pop song that has an ear-catching rhythmical guitar intro. The fourth track \"Red Dress\" is a dominant dance-pop track with lots of synth element running through the song, clapping-like [[Snare drum|snare]] and [[Marching band|marching]]-influenced [[drumline]] which tells a story in which a girl wears a red dress and clumsily but slyly tempts a man who treats her only as a child. The soulful, R&B-flavored \"Oh Boy\" showcases the singing ability and highlights harmonization of the girlgroup, while being the next three songs which are produced by LDN Noise. Ryan S. Jhun co-produced the former two tracks, with additional production by [[Denzil \"DR\" Remedios]] on \"Campfire\" and Dsign Music on \"Red Dress\". \n\nThe latter half of ''The Red'' starts with the sixth track \"Lady's Room\", an uptempo R&B, [[synth-pop]] song that sings about the sisterhood between girls and the happy moments they share. It was one of three tracks produced by [[Deekay|Daniel \"Obi\" Klein]] along with the next track \"Time Slip\", which is a 90s-influenced [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]-based R&B song with lyrics that describes the laziness and listlessness that one feels while going back and forth between dream and reality in the morning. \"Time Slip\" also sees the participation of British songwriter Charli Taft, whom had previously co-written and produced \"[[Automatic (Red Velvet song)|Automatic]]\" along with Daniel Klein, while marking the first collaboration from South Korean music producer Jinbo for the girl group. The eighth track \"Don't U Wait No More\" highlights the group's harmonization over a heavy synth production with a harmonized \"Don't you wait no more\" [[Hook (music)|hook]], with the lyrics revolve around a girl trying to get closer to her hesitant boyfriend, followed by the [[bossa nova]]-influenced [[midtempo]] pop-rock track \"Day 1\", which describes the feeling of new love by combining the electric, funky guitar sound and the melodic piano with the vocals of the members. The album ends with \"Cool World\", a [[synth-pop]] uptempo song with hopeful lyrics about embracing and living as themselves. \n\n==Promotion==\nPromoting activities for the album started with a \"[[Comeback (K-pop)|comeback showcase]]\" by Red Velvet where they performed \"Dumb Dumb.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=213&aid=0000755959&lfrom=twitter|title=\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3 \uc774\ubc88 \ucef4\ubc31\uc73c\ub85c \uccab \uc2dc\ub3c4\ud558\ub294 \uac83\ub4e4|author=Kim Ye-na|date=September 4, 2015|website=TV Report|language=Korean|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> They also appeared on a 5-episode live broadcast through the [[Naver]] V-Live [[Mobile app|app]] called ''\uc624\ubc29\ub9cc\uc871! (Satisfying five senses!) Red vs Velvet'' where they discussed the various concepts of their new album. The first episode was broadcast on September 7. The 2nd episode was broadcast on September 8, with [[SHINee]]'s [[Key (singer)|Key]] as the [[MC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/662329|title=\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3, 'V' \ud1b5\ud574 \ub9e4\ub825 \ub05d\ud310\uc655 \ub4f1\uadf9 \uc608\uace0\u2026'\uc624\ubc29\ub9cc\uc871! Red VS Velvet' \uc9c4\ud589|author=Jeong Si-woo|date=September 5, 2015|website=10asia|language=Korean|accessdate=September 5, 2015}}</ref> The group made their first comeback stage on ''[[M! Countdown]]'' on September 10, followed by performances on ''[[Music Bank (TV series)|Music Bank]]'', ''[[Show! Music Core]]'' and ''[[Inkigayo]]''. The group also performed a shortened version \"Huff 'n' Puff\" on the shows during their first promoting week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=404&aid=0000111990|title=\ub808\ub4dc\ubca8\ubcb3,10\uc77c '\uc5e0\uce74' \ud1b5\ud574 \uccab \ubc29\uc1a1\u2026\ud2b9\uae09 \ub9e4\ub825 \ubc1c\uc0b0 \uc608\uace0|author=Jeon Su-mi|date=September 5, 2015|website=enews24|language=Korean|accessdate=September 7, 2015}}</ref> ''The Red'' was further promoted by Red Velvet on their ''Red Room'' Asia tour in 2017, alongside their other releases from 2014 to their latest release ''[[The Red Summer (EP)|The Red Summer]]'' at the time.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = ''[[IZM]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.izm.co.kr/contentRead.asp?idx=27106&bigcateidx=1&subcateidx=3&view_tp=1&view_sort=1|accessdate=September, 2014 |website=IZM|author=Kim Do-hyun|publisher=IZM|title=The Red|language=korean}}</ref>\n| rev1Score = {{rating|2.5|5}}\n| rev1score = \n| rev2 = ''Seoulbeats''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://seoulbeats.com/2015/09/red-velvet-expands-on-boldness-in-the-red/|accessdate=September, 2014 |website=Seoulbeats|author=Lo|publisher=Seoulbeats|title=The Red|language=English}}</ref>\n| rev2score = {{rating|3.5|5}}\n}}Upon its release, ''The Red'' received positive reviews from critics for the group embracing their \"quirky\" side. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s Jeff Benjamin called ''The Red'' \"an impressive, solid debut album\" and stated that it \"indicates big things for the act that needs to follow in the footsteps of their beloved female label mates [[Girls' Generation]] and [[f(x) (band)|f(x)]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Benjamin|first=Jeff|title=Red Velvet Drop Brassy 'Dumb Dumb' Single, Quirky 'Red' Album|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/6692444/red-velvet-dumb-mv-red-album|website=Billboard|accessdate=December 23, 2015|date=September 9, 2015}}</ref> while ''[[Noisey]]'' stated that it's \"perhaps the strongest top-to-bottom K-pop album to date,\" praising its \"daredevil song forms, harmonies richer and smarter than anything on western dials in a quarter-century, and nonstop virtuoso songsmith hooks\u2014without so much as a single English inflection out of place.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Dorof|first=Jakob|title=2015 WAS THE YEAR K-POP NAILED THE FULL-LENGTH ALBUM|url=http://noisey.vice.com/en_au/blog/the-year-in-k-pop-2015-album-essay|website=Billboard|accessdate=December 23, 2015|date=December 16, 2015}}</ref> A review from Seoulbeats stated that ''The Red'' did \"live up\" to the expectations of the group's earlier \"Red\" releases, while praising the potential of the group's vocal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://seoulbeats.com/2015/09/red-velvet-expands-on-boldness-in-the-red/|title=Red Velvet Expands On Boldness In \u2018The Red\u2019|date=2015-09-14|website=Seoulbeats|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> In a mixed review from ''[[IZM]]'', writer Kim Do-hyun commented that the album \"should have been accompanied with more careful judgments\", giving the album two and a half stars, though highlighting tracks like \"Campfire\", \"Oh Boy\", \"Day 1\" and \"Cool World\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.izm.co.kr/contentRead.asp?idx=27106&bigcateidx=1&subcateidx=3&view_tp=1&view_sort=1|title=Neo Music Communication IZM|website=www.izm.co.kr|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>  ''Billboard'' also included it in their '10 Best K-Pop Albums of 2015' and called it \"one of the year's most enjoyable and experimental pop LPs.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benjamin|first1=Jeff|last2=Oak|first2=Jessica|title=The 10 Best K-Pop Albums of 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/6828137/best-k-pop-albums-2015|website=Billboard|accessdate=January 11, 2016|date=December 30, 2015}}</ref> The single \"Dumb Dumb\" was later included at #70 on ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s list of 100 Greatest Girl Group Songs of All Time, praising its hooks and being one of \"the most addictive singles in pop\".<ref>{{cite web|title=100 Greatest Girl Group Songs of All Time: Critics' Picks|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7857816/100-greatest-girl-group-songs|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> In a separated top 25 Red Velvet songs by ''Billboard'', four songs from ''The Red'' made its appearance, including \"Dumb Dumb\" at No. 4, \"Cool World\" at No. 13, \"Time Slip\" at No. 15, and lastly \"Red Dress\" at No. 21.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8525588/best-red-velvet-songs-critics-picks|title=Red Velvet's 25 Best Songs|date=2019-07-31|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nOn the week of September 6, 2015, ''The Red'' debuted and topped the weekly [[Gaon Album Chart]] for one week, becoming the group's second chart-topper in 2015 after their [[Ice Cream Cake (EP)|debut extended play]] in March 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/|title=Gaon Album Chart - Week 38/2015|last=|first=|date=|website=gaonchart.co.kr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> The entire ten tracks also charted on the Gaon Digital Chart in the same week. With 46,571 copies sold, ''The Red'' was the 53th best-selling album in 2015 on the year-end Gaon Album Chart, and has since achieved a cumulative sales of almost 80,000 copies as of August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/|title=2015's Gaon Year-End Album Chart|last=|first=|date=|website=gaonchart.co.kr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> It also attained success in the United States, becoming their first release to top the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard's]]'' World Albums Chart, and peaked at number twenty-four on its [[Top Heatseekers|Heatseekers Albums chart]], having achieved a total sales of 3,000 copies as of March 30, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8275948/red-velvet-south-korean-kpop-group-get-to-know-10-facts|title=Red Velvet Performs in North Korea: 10 Things to Know for the Historic K-Pop Performance|date=2018-03-30|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> Elsewhere, the album also debuted and peaked at No. 47 on the Japanese [[Oricon Albums Chart]], earning a total sales of almost 4,500 copies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916072003/http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/ja/w/2015-09-21/p/5/|title=\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3\u9031\u9593 CD\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 2015\u5e7409\u670807\u65e5\uff5e2015\u5e7409\u670813\u65e5 41\uff5e50\u4f4d {{!}} ORICON STYLE|date=2015-09-16|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n\nThe music video for \"Dumb Dumb\" debuted at #1 on [[YinYueTai]]'s V-Chart Korea. It is also the most viewed [[k-pop]] video in America and worldwide for the month of September. ''[[Dazed|Dazed Digital]]'' named \"Dumb Dumb\" their top [[K-pop]] track of 2015. In December, \"Dumb Dumb\" was included in ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone's]]'' '10 Best Music Videos of 2015'.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline       = ''The Red''\n| total_length   = 33:13\n| title1         = [[Dumb Dumb]]\n| lyrics1        = Seo Ji-eum ([[Jam Factory]]), Kim Dong-hyun\n| music1         = [[LDN Noise]], Deanna Dellacioppa, Taylor Parks, [[Ryan S. Jhun]]\n| length1        = 3:22\n| title2         = Huff n Puff\n| lyrics2        = [[Kenzie (songwriter)|Kenzie]]\n| music2         = Alex G, Anne Preven, Will Gray, Jaden Michaels\n| length2        = 3:01\n\n| title3         = Campfire\n| lyrics3        = Jo Yun-kyeong\n| music3         =  LDN Noise, Taylor Parks, Denzil \"DR\" Remedios, Ryan S. Jhun\n| length3        = 3:16\n\n| title4         = Red Dress\n| lyrics4        = Jo Yun-kyeong\n| music4         = [[Dsign Music|Nermin Harambasic, Jin Suk Choi, Charite Viken]], LDN Noise, Rodnae \"Chikk\" Bell, Ryan S. Jhun\n| length4        = 3:02\n\n| title5         = Oh Boy\n| lyrics5        = Goo Tae-woo\n| music5         = Herbie Crichlow, Lauren Dyson, [[Dsign Music|Jin Suk Choi]], LDN Noise\n| length5        = 3:08\n\n| title6         = Lady's Room\n| lyrics6        = [[Kenzie (songwriter)|Kenzie]]\n| music6         = [[Kenzie (songwriter)|Kenzie]], [[Deekay|Daniel \"Obi\" Klein]], Oliver McEwan, Ylva Dimberg\n| length6        = 3:15\n\n| title7         = Time Slip\n| lyrics7        = Moon Du-ri\n| music7         = Daniel \"Obi\" Klein, [[Deekay|Johannes \"Josh\" Jorgensen]], [[Charli Taft]], Jinbo\n| length7        = 3:39\n\n| title8         = Don't U Wait No More\n| lyrics8        = 100%Seo-jeong (Jam Factory)\n| music8         = [[Dem Jointz|Dwayne Abernathy Jr., (Dem Jointz)]] [[Taylor Parks]], Ryan S. Jhun\n| length8        = 2:51\n\n| title9         = Day 1\n| lyrics9        = Hwang-hyun (MonoTree)\n| music9         = Hwang-hyun (MonoTree)\n| length9        = 3:26\n\n| title10        = Cool World\n| lyrics10       = Im Seo-hyun\n| music10        = Daniel \"Obi\" Klein, Marcus Winther-John, Andy Love\n| length10       = 4:05\n}}\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart (2015)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Japanese Albums ([[Oricon]])<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150928031204/http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/ja/w/2015-09-21/p/5/ Japan's [[Oricon]] Chart from September 7\u201313, 2015 (in Korean)] Originally from [[Oricon]] (September 2015). Archiv