{"title_page": "Damodar Kashinath Jatar", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Captain\n| name               = Damodar Kashinath Jatar\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]]\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = [[Indian]]\n| citizenship        = {{Flag|India}}\n| occupation         = [[Pilot]]\n| awards             = [[File:Ashoka Chakra ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra]]\n}}\n\nCaptain '''Damodar Kashinath Jatar''', [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]] was an experienced pilot of the Air India International Corporation who was posthumously awarded with India's highest peacetime gallantry award [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra]]. He was the first Indian civilian  who got Ashoka Chakra.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=D. K Jatar|title=Beyond the last Blue Mountain|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=LcUDAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT170&lpg=PT170&dq=D+K+Jatar+ashoka+chakra&source=bl&ots=zy3y6nnNI1&sig=ACfU3U3toBGvNr2_FoegcXPvw856z-pH7g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiHkJbt2ozpAhUZcCsKHbYRDEs4ChDoATANegQIBhAB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gallantryawards.gov.in/Awardee/d-k-jatar|title=D.K Jatar {{!}} Gallantry Award|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Gallant act ==\nOn April 11, 1955, he was piloting Air India International Corporation's Constellation aircraft, \"[[Kashmir Princess]]\", from [[Hong Kong]] to [[Jakarta]] on a special chartered flight, carrying, amongst others, some Chinese delegates who were to join the Afro- Asian Conference at Bandung. At about 4 hours 53 minutes local time, when the aircraft was at an altitude of 16,460 metres, in the vicinity of Natuna Island in the South China Sea, an explosion took place in the starboard wheel-well. Soon afterwards, an intense fire developed and spread rapidly over the right wing of the plane, while the whole interior of the aircraft, including the cockpit, was filled with smoke. The situation was very grave as there was no landing ground within about 160 km. Without hesitation or fear, the brave pilot decided to ditch his plane. He carried out all precautionary measures for the emergency landing and gave quick and precise orders in a cool and unperturbed manner which commanded instantaneous obedience from all members of the crew. And this eliminated panic and confusion. He also made a quick and accurate selection of the spot for ditching the aircraft in the sea. It was this brave decision, which unfortunately resulted in the self-sacrifice of the Captain, but saved three lives by enabling the survivors to reach the shore.\n\n== Ashoka Chakra awardee ==\nCaptain D.K. Jatar was posthumously awarded the [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra]], the highest civilian gallantry award of independent India. Captain Jatar, thus, became the first civilian recipient of this gallantry award for his bravery and supreme sacrifice.\n\n== Reference ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ashoka Chakra award recipients}}\n\n[[Category:Recipients of the Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)]]\n[[Category:Ashoka Chakra]]\n", "text_old": "{{Proposed deletion/dated\n  |concern = News of a single event is not encyclopedic content\n  |timestamp = 20200429094526\n  |help = off\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Captain\n| name               = Damodar Kashinath Jatar\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]]\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = [[Indian]]\n| citizenship        = {{Flag|India}}\n| occupation         = [[Pilot]]\n| awards             = [[File:Ashoka Chakra ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra]]\n}}\n\nCaptain '''Damodar Kashinath Jatar''', [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]] was an experienced pilot of the Air India International Corporation who was posthumously awarded with India's highest peacetime gallantry award [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra]]. He was the first Indian civilian  who got Ashoka Chakra.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=D. K Jatar|title=Beyond the last Blue Mountain|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=LcUDAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT170&lpg=PT170&dq=D+K+Jatar+ashoka+chakra&source=bl&ots=zy3y6nnNI1&sig=ACfU3U3toBGvNr2_FoegcXPvw856z-pH7g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiHkJbt2ozpAhUZcCsKHbYRDEs4ChDoATANegQIBhAB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gallantryawards.gov.in/Awardee/d-k-jatar|title=D.K Jatar {{!}} Gallantry Award|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n== Gallant act ==\nOn April 11, 1955, he was piloting Air India International Corporation's Constellation aircraft, \"[[Kashmir Princess]]\", from [[Hong Kong]] to [[Jakarta]] on a special chartered flight, carrying, amongst others, some Chinese delegates who were to join the Afro- Asian Conference at Bandung. At about 4 hours 53 minutes local time, when the aircraft was at an altitude of 16,460 metres, in the vicinity of Natuna Island in the South China Sea, an explosion took place in the starboard wheel-well. Soon afterwards, an intense fire developed and spread rapidly over the right wing of the plane, while the whole interior of the aircraft, including the cockpit, was filled with smoke. The situation was very grave as there was no landing ground within about 160 km. Without hesitation or fear, the brave pilot decided to ditch his plane. He carried out all precautionary measures for the emergency landing and gave quick and precise orders in a cool and unperturbed manner which commanded instantaneous obedience from all members of the crew. And this eliminated panic and confusion. He also made a quick and accurate selection of the spot for ditching the aircraft in the sea. It was this brave decision, which unfortunately resulted in the self-sacrifice of the Captain, but saved three lives by enabling the survivors to reach the shore.\n\n== Ashoka Chakra awardee ==\nCaptain D.K. Jatar was posthumously awarded the [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra]], the highest civilian gallantry award of independent India. Captain Jatar, thus, became the first civilian recipient of this gallantry award for his bravery and supreme sacrifice.\n\n== Reference ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ashoka Chakra award recipients}}\n\n[[Category:Recipients of the Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)]]\n[[Category:Ashoka Chakra]]\n", "name_user": "Koushik Pain", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damodar_Kashinath_Jatar"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Ornoch", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Andrew Ornoch\n| image                = Andrew Ornoch.jpg\n| fullname             = Andrzej Mateusz Ornoch\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1985|8|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Warsaw]], Poland\n| height               = 1.90 m\n| position             = [[striker (association football)|Midfielder/Forward]]\n| currentclub          = \n| clubnumber           = \n| youthyears1          = 1995\u20131999\n| youthclubs1          = North Scarborough\n| youthyears2          = 1999\u20132001\n| youthclubs2          = PSA Toronto\n| youthyears4          = 2002\u20132005\n| youthclubs4          = Erin Mills\n| youthyears5          = 2003\u20132005\n| youthclubs5          = [[University of Detroit Mercy]]\n| years1               = 2002\n| clubs1               = [[Mississauga Olympians]]\n| caps1                = 2\n| goals1               = 0\n| years2               = 2005\u20132008\n| clubs2               = [[Lombard-P\u00e1pa TFC|Lombard-P\u00e1pa]]\n| caps2                = 34\n| goals2               = 10\n| years3               = 2008\u20132009\n| clubs3               = [[Esbjerg fB|Esbjerg]]\n| caps3                = 13\n| goals3               = 1\n| years4               = 2009\u20132010\n| clubs4               = [[Heracles Almelo|Heracles]]\n| caps4                = 1\n| goals4               = 0\n| years5               = 2010\n| clubs5               = [[BV Veendam|Veendam]]\n| caps5                = 9\n| goals5               = 3\n| years6               = 2011\n| clubs6               = [[Mississauga Eagles FC|Mississauga Eagles]]\n| caps6                = 3\n| goals6               = 1\n| years7               = 2011\n| clubs7               = [[SC Telstar|Telstar]]\n| caps7                = 7\n| goals7               = 1\n| years8               = 2014\n| clubs8               = Vaughan Azzurri\n| caps8                = \n| goals8               = 10\n| nationalyears1       = 2006\u20132009\n| nationalteam1        = [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]]\n| nationalcaps1        = 3\n| nationalgoals1       = 0\n| medaltemplates       =\n| pcupdate             = 7 October 2017\n| ntupdate             = 30 December 2009\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Ornoch''' (born 21 August 1985 in [[Warsaw]]) is a [[Poland|Polish]]-born Canadian former professional footballer who played in the [[Canadian Professional Soccer League (1998-2005)|Canadian Professional Soccer League]], [[Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I]], [[Danish Superliga]], [[Eredivisie]], [[Eerste Divisie]], [[Canadian Soccer League]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early years===\n\nHe attended St. John Fisher Catholic elementary school and [[Pope John Paul II Catholic Secondary School]] in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]], [[Ontario]]. As a [[midfielder]] he began playing football for the renowned North Scarborough Soccer Club, known for producing international players such as [[Juli\u00e1n de Guzm\u00e1n]] formerly of [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]], [[Jonathan de Guzm\u00e1n]] of [[Feyenoord]], [[Atiba Hutchinson]] of [[F.C. Copenhagen]] and [[Dave Simpson (soccer)|Dave Simpson]] of [[Sparta Prague]]. From there he went on to [[Erin Mills Soccer Club]], one of Canada's leading clubs that also produced players such as Dave Simpson. After which he earned an Athletic Scholarship to the [[University of Detroit Mercy]] where he was named [[Horizon League]] player of the year and offensive player of the year in 2005 on the way to leading the team to its first ever Horizon League Championship. He is the 4th All-Time top scorer in the History of University of Detroit Mercy.<ref>[http://www.detroittitans.com/msoccer.jsp?id=1165259773887 University of Detroit Mercy] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070520091042/http://www.detroittitans.com/msoccer.jsp?id=1165259773887 |date=20 May 2007 }}</ref> Ornoch began his professional career with a brief stint with the [[Mississauga Olympians]] in the [[Canadian Professional Soccer League (1998-2005)|Canadian Professional Soccer League]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canadiansoccerleague.ca/where-are-they-now-csl-players-moving-up/|title=WHERE ARE THEY NOW \u2026\u2026.CSL players moving up \u2013 Canadian Soccer League|last=Adamson|first=Stan|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-07}}</ref> He made his debut for the club on 4 October 2002 against the [[Vaughan Sun Devils]] coming on as a substitute for [[Darren Tilley]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = October 4, 2002 CPSL Vaughan Sun Devils vs Mississauga Olympians (by Rocket Robin)|url = http://www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com/reports02/02cpsl1e.htm|website = www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com|accessdate = 2015-04-15|last = Glover|first = Robin}}</ref>\n\n===Lombard-P\u00e1pa===\nIn the spring of 2006 Andrew Ornoch departed from school a year early in order to play professional soccer in the [[Hungarian National Championship I|Borsodi liga]], the top division in [[Hungary]]. Soon after Andrew joined [[Lombard-P\u00e1pa TFC]], where compatriot [[Dave Simpson (soccer)|Dave Simpson]] also played, the team was relegated due to financial issues. He stayed with P\u00e1pa a full season at the [[Hungarian National Championship II|Hungarian 2nd level]] but left them halfway his 2nd season.\n\n===Esbjerg===\nIn 2008 Andrew went on to sign a 4-year contract with [[Esbjerg fB]] in the [[Danish Superliga]] where he joined fellow Canadians [[Atiba Hutchinson]] of [[F.C. Copenhagen|Copenhagen]] and [[Issey Nakajima|Issey Nakajima-Farran]] of [[FC Nordsj\u00e6lland|Nordsj\u00e6lland]].\n\n===Heracles Almelo===\nOn 30 August 2009 he joined Dutch club [[Heracles Almelo]],<ref>[http://www.tctubantia.nl/regio/5445703/Andrzej-Ornoch-naar-Heracles-Almelo.ece Andrzej Ornoch naar Heracles Almelo] \u2013 Twentsche Coutans Tubantia {{in lang|nl}}</ref> a former club of another fellow countryman, [[Rob Friend]]. On 26 August 2010, Ornoch joined Dutch Jupiler League club [[BV Veendam]] and scored his first goal in his second appearance versus [[FC Emmen|Emmen]] on 3 September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bvveendam.nl/nieuws/828-nieuwe-spits-is-binnen-andrew-ornoch.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721105940/http://www.bvveendam.nl/nieuws/828-nieuwe-spits-is-binnen-andrew-ornoch.html |archivedate=21 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> It was heavily rumoured that Ornoch was set to sign for [[Toronto FC]] of [[Major League Soccer]] prior to the 2011 season. However, in late January it was released that the deal fell through due to [[Aron Winter]], the coaches lack of interest. Several sources say that Ornoch was upset by the decision, claiming that TFC advised him to buy himself out of his contract in Europe before pulling an implied offer off the table.<ref>[http://www.canadiansoccernews.com/content.php?1055-Reds-say-no-to-Andrew-OrnochReds say no to Andrew Ornoch; look likely to add Brazilian]</ref>\n\n===Return To Europe, SC Telstar===\nAfter a brief stint in the [[Canadian Soccer League]] with [[Mississauga Eagles FC]] Ornoch returned to the Netherlands to play in the [[Eerste Divisie]] with [[Telstar (football club)|Telstar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://erinmillssoccer.com/news/club-news/year-one-csl-mefc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160205115448/http://erinmillssoccer.com/news/club-news/year-one-csl-mefc|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-02-05|title=\"Year One\" in the CSL for MEFC: What a Ride! {{!}} Erin Mills Soccer Club|date=2016-02-05|access-date=2017-02-10}}</ref> He made his debut for the team on 5 August 2011 against [[FC Dordrecht]] scoring one goal, the game ended in a 3\u20130 victory for Telstar.\n\n==International career==\nOrnoch made his debut for [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] in a November 2006 friendly match against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]], the country where he then played his club football. By December 2009, he earned a total of 3 caps, all as a sub, scoring no goals. He has so far represented Canada in 1 [[FIFA World Cup qualification]] match.<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player=295921/index.html Record at FIFA Tournaments] \u2013 FIFA</ref>\n\n==Dutch Connections FC==\nOrnoch founded a football camp for youth along with [[J\u00f6rg van Nieuwenhuijzen]] to help kids in Canada improve their skills using a Dutch approach. [http://www.dutchconnectionsfc.com Dutch Connections FC] offers the best player from each camp a trial with a professional club in the Netherlands.<ref>[http://www.rednationonline.ca/RedNationInterviewsAndrewOrnoch.aspx RedNation Online]</ref> Van Nieuwenhuijzen and Ornoch played together for [[Heracles Almelo]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.efb.dk/nc/fodbold/truppen/spillervisning.html?tx_wkleague_pi1%5BplayerID%5D%3D409 |title=Player profile \u2013 Esbjerg fB |access-date=24 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106054235/http://www.efb.dk/nc/fodbold/truppen/spillervisning.html?tx_wkleague_pi1%5BplayerID%5D%3D409 |archive-date=6 January 2009 |url-status=bot: unknown }}\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.detroittitans.com/msoccer.jsp?id=1165259773887 |title=University of Detroit Mercy |access-date=14 March 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070520091042/http://www.detroittitans.com/msoccer.jsp?id=1165259773887 |archive-date=20 May 2007 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.erinmillssoccer.com/league.php?scriptName=LEAGUEINFO&leagueID=6451&leagueInfoID=35935&cache=no |title=Erin Mills Commemorates Andrew Ornoch |access-date=14 March 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928182024/http://www.erinmillssoccer.com/league.php?scriptName=LEAGUEINFO&leagueID=6451&leagueInfoID=35935&cache=no |archive-date=28 September 2007 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.heracles.nl/selectie/informatie?Seizoen=2009-2010&SpelerId=123 |title=Player profile \u2013 Heracles Almelo |access-date=30 December 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724154351/http://www.heracles.nl/selectie/informatie?Seizoen=2009-2010&SpelerId=123 |archive-date=24 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{NFT player|24386}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ornoch, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Warsaw]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Canada]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Canadian Professional Soccer League (1998\u20132005) players]]\n[[Category:Canadian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Canada men's international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Canadian Soccer League (2006\u2013present) players]]\n[[Category:Polish footballers]]\n[[Category:Polish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Polish expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Polish expatriate sportspeople in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Polish expatriate sportspeople in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Polish expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Toronto (Mississauga) Olympians players]]\n[[Category:Lombard-P\u00e1pa TFC footballers]]\n[[Category:Esbjerg fB players]]\n[[Category:Heracles Almelo players]]\n[[Category:SC Veendam players]]\n[[Category:SC Telstar players]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:League1 Ontario players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Detroit Mercy Titans men's soccer players]]\n[[Category:Mississauga Eagles FC players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Andrew Ornoch\n| image                = Andrew Ornoch.jpg\n| fullname             = Andrzej Mateusz Ornoch\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1985|8|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Warsaw]], Poland\n| height               = 1.90 m\n| position             = [[striker (association football)|Midfielder/Forward]]\n| currentclub          = \n| clubnumber           = \n| youthyears1          = 1995\u20131999\n| youthclubs1          = North Scarborough\n| youthyears2          = 1999\u20132001\n| youthclubs2          = PSA Toronto\n| youthyears4          = 2002\u20132005\n| youthclubs4          = Erin Mills\n| youthyears5          = 2003\u20132005\n| youthclubs5          = [[University of Detroit Mercy]]\n| years1               = 2002\n| clubs1               = [[Mississauga Olympians]]\n| caps1                = 2\n| goals1               = 0\n| years2               = 2005\u20132008\n| clubs2               = [[Lombard-P\u00e1pa TFC|Lombard-P\u00e1pa]]\n| caps2                = 34\n| goals2               = 10\n| years3               = 2008\u20132009\n| clubs3               = [[Esbjerg fB|Esbjerg]]\n| caps3                = 13\n| goals3               = 1\n| years4               = 2009\u20132010\n| clubs4               = [[Heracles Almelo|Heracles]]\n| caps4                = 1\n| goals4               = 0\n| years5               = 2010\n| clubs5               = [[BV Veendam|Veendam]]\n| caps5                = 9\n| goals5               = 3\n| years6               = 2011\n| clubs6               = [[Mississauga Eagles FC|Mississauga Eagles]]\n| caps6                = 3\n| goals6               = 1\n| years7               = 2011\n| clubs7               = [[SC Telstar|Telstar]]\n| caps7                = 7\n| goals7               = 1\n| years8               = 2014\n| clubs8               = Vaughan Azzurri\n| caps8                = \n| goals8               = 10\n| nationalyears1       = 2006\u20132009\n| nationalteam1        = [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]]\n| nationalcaps1        = 3\n| nationalgoals1       = 0\n| medaltemplates       =\n| pcupdate             = 7 October 2017\n| ntupdate             = 30 December 2009\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Ornoch''' (born 21 August 1985 in [[Warsaw]]) is a [[Poland|Polish]]-born Canadian former professional footballer who played in the [[Canadian Professional Soccer League (1998-2005)|Canadian Professional Soccer League]], [[Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I]], [[Danish Superliga]], [[Eredivisie]], [[Eerste Divisie]], [[Canadian Soccer League]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early years===\n\nHe attended St. John Fisher Catholic elementary school and [[Pope John Paul II Catholic Secondary School]] in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]], [[Ontario]]. As a [[midfielder]] he began playing football for the renowned North Scarborough Soccer Club, known for producing international players such as [[Juli\u00e1n de Guzm\u00e1n]] formerly of [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]], [[Jonathan de Guzm\u00e1n]] of [[Feyenoord]], [[Atiba Hutchinson]] of [[F.C. Copenhagen]] and [[Dave Simpson (soccer)|Dave Simpson]] of [[Sparta Prague]]. From there he went on to [[Erin Mills Soccer Club]], one of Canada's leading clubs that also produced players such as Dave Simpson. After which he earned an Athletic Scholarship to the [[University of Detroit Mercy]] where he was named [[Horizon League]] player of the year and offensive player of the year in 2005 on the way to leading the team to its first ever Horizon League Championship. He is the 4th All-Time top scorer in the History of University of Detroit Mercy.<ref>[http://www.detroittitans.com/msoccer.jsp?id=1165259773887 University of Detroit Mercy] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070520091042/http://www.detroittitans.com/msoccer.jsp?id=1165259773887 |date=20 May 2007 }}</ref> Ornoch began his professional career with a brief stint with the [[Mississauga Olympians]] in the [[Canadian Professional Soccer League (1998-2005)|Canadian Professional Soccer League]] in 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canadiansoccerleague.ca/where-are-they-now-csl-players-moving-up/|title=WHERE ARE THEY NOW \u2026\u2026.CSL players moving up \u2013 Canadian Soccer League|last=Adamson|first=Stan|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-07}}</ref> He made his debut for the club on 4 October 2002 against the [[Vaughan Sun Devils]] coming on as a substitute for [[Darren Tilley]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = October 4, 2002 CPSL Vaughan Sun Devils vs Mississauga Olympians (by Rocket Robin)|url = http://www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com/reports02/02cpsl1e.htm|website = www.rocketrobinsoccerintoronto.com|accessdate = 2015-04-15|last = Glover|first = Robin}}</ref>\n\n===Lombard-P\u00e1pa===\nIn the spring of 2006 Andrew Ornoch departed from school a year early in order to play professional soccer in the [[Hungarian National Championship I|Borsodi liga]], the top division in [[Hungary]]. Soon after Andrew joined [[Lombard-P\u00e1pa TFC]], where compatriot [[Dave Simpson (soccer)|Dave Simpson]] also played, the team was relegated due to financial issues. He stayed with P\u00e1pa a full season at the [[Hungarian National Championship II|Hungarian 2nd level]] but left them halfway his 2nd season.\n\n===Esbjerg===\nIn 2008 Andrew went on to sign a 4-year contract with [[Esbjerg fB]] in the [[Danish Superliga]] where he joined fellow Canadians [[Atiba Hutchinson]] of [[F.C. Copenhagen|Copenhagen]] and [[Issey Nakajima|Issey Nakajima-Farran]] of [[FC Nordsj\u00e6lland|Nordsj\u00e6lland]].\n\n===Heracles Almelo===\nOn 30 August 2009 he joined Dutch club [[Heracles Almelo]],<ref>[http://www.tctubantia.nl/regio/5445703/Andrzej-Ornoch-naar-Heracles-Almelo.ece Andrzej Ornoch naar Heracles Almelo] \u2013 Twentsche Coutans Tubantia {{in lang|nl}}</ref> a former club of another fellow countryman, [[Rob Friend]]. On 26 August 2010, Ornoch joined Dutch Jupiler League club [[BV Veendam]] and scored his first goal in his second appearance versus [[FC Emmen|Emmen]] on 3 September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bvveendam.nl/nieuws/828-nieuwe-spits-is-binnen-andrew-ornoch.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721105940/http://www.bvveendam.nl/nieuws/828-nieuwe-spits-is-binnen-andrew-ornoch.html |archivedate=21 July 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> It was heavily rumoured that Ornoch was set to sign for [[Toronto FC]] of [[Major League Soccer]] prior to the 2011 season. However, in late January it was released that the deal fell through due to [[Aron Winter]], the coaches lack of interest. Several sources say that Ornoch was upset by the decision, claiming that TFC advised him to buy himself out of his contract in Europe before pulling an implied offer off the table.<ref>[http://www.canadiansoccernews.com/content.php?1055-Reds-say-no-to-Andrew-OrnochReds say no to Andrew Ornoch; look likely to add Brazilian]</ref>\n\n===Return To Europe, SC Telstar===\nAfter a brief stint in the [[Canadian Soccer League]] with [[Mississauga Eagles FC]] Ornoch returned to the Netherlands to play in the [[Eerste Divisie]] with [[Telstar (football club)|Telstar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://erinmillssoccer.com/news/club-news/year-one-csl-mefc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160205115448/http://erinmillssoccer.com/news/club-news/year-one-csl-mefc|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-02-05|title=\"Year One\" in the CSL for MEFC: What a Ride! {{!}} Erin Mills Soccer Club|date=2016-02-05|access-date=2017-02-10}}</ref> He made his debut for the team on 5 August 2011 against [[FC Dordrecht]] scoring one goal, the game ended in a 3\u20130 victory for Telstar.\n\n==International career==\nOrnoch made his debut for [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] in a November 2006 friendly match against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]], the country where he then played his club football. By December 2009, he earned a total of 3 caps, all as a sub, scoring no goals. He has so far represented Canada in 1 [[FIFA World Cup qualification]] match.<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player=295921/index.html Record at FIFA Tournaments] \u2013 FIFA</ref>\n\n==Dutch Connections FC==\nOrnoch founded a football camp for youth along with [[J\u00f6rg van Nieuwenhuijzen]] to help kids in Canada improve their skills using a Dutch approach. [http://www.dutchconnectionsfc.com Dutch Connections FC] offers the best player from each camp a trial with a professional club in the Netherlands.<ref>[http://www.rednationonline.ca/RedNationInterviewsAndrewOrnoch.aspx RedNation Online]</ref> Van Nieuwenhuijzen and Ornoch played together for [[Heracles Almelo]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.efb.dk/nc/fodbold/truppen/spillervisning.html?tx_wkleague_pi1%5BplayerID%5D%3D409 |title=Player profile \u2013 Esbjerg fB |access-date=24 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106054235/http://www.efb.dk/nc/fodbold/truppen/spillervisning.html?tx_wkleague_pi1%5BplayerID%5D%3D409 |archive-date=6 January 2009 |url-status=bot: unknown }}\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.detroittitans.com/msoccer.jsp?id=1165259773887 |title=University of Detroit Mercy |access-date=14 March 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070520091042/http://www.detroittitans.com/msoccer.jsp?id=1165259773887 |archive-date=20 May 2007 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.erinmillssoccer.com/league.php?scriptName=LEAGUEINFO&leagueID=6451&leagueInfoID=35935&cache=no |title=Erin Mills Commemorates Andrew Ornoch |access-date=14 March 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928182024/http://www.erinmillssoccer.com/league.php?scriptName=LEAGUEINFO&leagueID=6451&leagueInfoID=35935&cache=no |archive-date=28 September 2007 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{Cite web |url=http://www.heracles.nl/selectie/informatie?Seizoen=2009-2010&SpelerId=123 |title=Player profile \u2013 Heracles Almelo |access-date=30 December 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724154351/http://www.heracles.nl/selectie/informatie?Seizoen=2009-2010&SpelerId=123 |archive-date=24 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{NFT player|24386}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ornoch, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Warsaw]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Canada]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Canadian Professional Soccer League (1998\u20132005) players]]\n[[Category:Canadian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Canada men's international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Canadian Soccer League (2006\u2013present) players]]\n[[Category:Polish footballers]]\n[[Category:Polish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Polish expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Polish expatriate sportspeople in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Polish expatriate sportspeople in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Polish expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Toronto (Mississauga) Olympians players]]\n[[Category:Lombard-P\u00e1pa TFC footballers]]\n[[Category:Esbjerg fB players]]\n[[Category:Heracles Almelo players]]\n[[Category:SC Veendam players]]\n[[Category:SC Telstar players]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:League1 Ontario players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Detroit Mercy Titans men's soccer players]]\n[[Category:Mississauga Eagles FC players]]\n", "name_user": "Severo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:AddingCategory:Footballers from Warsaw", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Ornoch"}
{"title_page": "Kim Nung-o", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Korean name|Kim}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         =  Pak Jong-nam\n|native_name  = \ubc15\uc815\ub0a8\n|image        = \n|office       = Chairman of WPK North Pyongyan Provincial Committee\n|blankname   = {{nowrap|[[Supreme Leader of North Korea|Supreme Leader]]}}\n|namedata    = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n|president    = \n|term_start   = 2016\n|term_end     = 2018\n|predecessor  = [[Ri Man-gon]]\n|successor    = [[Mun Kyong-dok]]\n|office1      = Chairman of WPK Pyongyang Provincial Committee\n|1blankname   = {{nowrap|[[Supreme Leader of North Korea|Supreme Leader]]}}\n|1namedata    = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n|president1    = \n|term_start1   = 2018\n|term_end1     = 2020\n|predecessor1  = [[Kim Su-gil]]\n|successor1    = [[Kim Yong-hwan (politician)|Kim Yong-hwan]]\n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = \n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| hangul    = {{linktext|\uae40|\ub2a5|\uc624}}\n| hanja     = {{linktext|\u91d1|\u80fd|\u4e94}}\n| rr        = Kim Neungo\n| mr        = Kim N\u016dng-o\n| koreanipa =\n| context   = north\n| image     =\n| caption   =\n| text      = <ref>{{Cite web |script-title=ko:\uae40\ub2a5\uc624(\ub0a8\uc131) |publisher=Ministry of Unification |work=nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr |access-date=21 March 2019 |url= http://nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr/nkp/theme/viewPeople.do?nkpmno=13966 |language=ko }}</ref><ref name=\"nkle_KimN\"/>\n}}\n'''Kim Nung-o''' ({{lang|ko|\uae40\ub2a5\uc624}}, born in the late 1960s) is a [[North Korea]]n politician. He is the chairman of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] (WPK) Party Committee of [[Pyongyang]]. Kim is also a full member of the [[Central Committee of the WPK]] and an alternate member of [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|its Politburo]].\n\n==Career==\nKim Nung-o was born in the late 1960s. He was educated at [[Kim Il-sung University]].<ref name=\"nkle_KimN\">{{Cite web |title=Kim Nung O |work=North Korea Leadership Watch |access-date=21 March 2019 |url= http://www.nkleadershipwatch.org/leadership-biographies/kim-nung-o/ |date=28 February 2018 }}</ref>\n\nKim has worked at various departments of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea]] (WPK), being a vice director of the [[Finance and Accounting Department]] in 2013. He was first mentioned by [[North Korean media]] on 1 November 2014 when he was accompanying [[Kim Jong-un]] on a [[guidance tour]] of [[Pyongyang International Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=November: Military and diplomatic focus, status of Kim\u2019s family |last=Grisafi |first=John G. |work=NK News |date=8 December 2014 |access-date=21 March 2019 |url= https://www.nknews.org/2014/12/november-military-and-diplomatic-focus-status-of-kims-family/ }}</ref> Kim Nung-o became the chief secretary of the Party Committee of [[North Pyongan Province]] in December 2015, replacing [[Ri Man-gon]]. He subsequently become the chairman of the Party Committee.<ref name=\"nkle_KimN\"/> He now serves as the chairman of the Party Committee of the capital [[Pyongyang]].<ref name=kyodonews>{{Cite web |title=North Koreans vow to fulfill tasks Kim Jong Un cited in New Year statement |agency=Kyodo News |date=4 January 2019 |access-date=21 March 2019 |url= https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2019/01/3bb367ad7210-north-koreans-vow-to-fulfill-tasks-kim-jong-un-mentioned-in-new-year-statement.html }}</ref>\n\nKim became a full member of the Central Committee and an alternate member of the [[Politburo of the WPK]] at the [[7th Congress of the WPK]] in May 2016.<ref name=\"nkle_KimN\"/> In January 2019, Kim gave a speech at a mass rally at [[Kim Il-sung Square]] in Pyongyang,<ref name=kyodonews/> praising Kim Jong-un's New Year Address and urging inhabitants of the city to increase efforts to attain a self-reliant socialist economy.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Pyongyang citizens rally in support of Supreme Leader\u2019s address |agency=KCNA |work=The Pyongyang Times |date= |access-date=21 March 2019 |url= http://www.pyongyangtimes.com.kp/?bbs=28714 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|North Korea}}\n* [[Politics of North Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ri Man-gon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairman of WPK North Pyongyan Provincial Committee|years=2016-2018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mun Kyong-dok]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Choe Ryong-hae]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairman of WPK Pyongyang Provincial Committee|years=2018\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kim Yong-hwan (politician)|Kim Yong-hwan]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kim, Nung-o}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:North Korean politicians]]\n[[Category:1960s births]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Korean name|Kim}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         =  Pak Jong-nam\n|native_name  = \ubc15\uc815\ub0a8\n|image        = \n|office       = Chairman of WPK North Pyongyan Provincial Committee\n|blankname   = {{nowrap|[[Supreme Leader of North Korea|Supreme Leader]]}}\n|namedata    = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n|president    = \n|term_start   = 2016\n|term_end     = 2018\n|predecessor  = [[Ri Man-gon]]\n|successor    = [[Mun Kyong-dok]]\n|office1      = Chairman of WPK Pyongyang Provincial Committee\n|1blankname   = {{nowrap|[[Supreme Leader of North Korea|Supreme Leader]]}}\n|1namedata    = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n|president1    = \n|term_start1   = 2018\n|term_end1     = 2020\n|predecessor1  = [[Kim Su-gil]]\n|successor1    = [[Kim Yong-hwan (politician)|Kim Yong-hwan]]\n|birth_date   = \n|birth_place  = \n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| hangul    = {{linktext|\uae40|\ub2a5|\uc624}}\n| hanja     = {{linktext|\u91d1|\u80fd|\u4e94}}\n| rr        = Kim Neungo\n| mr        = Kim N\u016dng-o\n| koreanipa =\n| context   = north\n| image     =\n| caption   =\n| text      = <ref>{{Cite web |script-title=ko:\uae40\ub2a5\uc624(\ub0a8\uc131) |publisher=Ministry of Unification |work=nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr |access-date=21 March 2019 |url= http://nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr/nkp/theme/viewPeople.do?nkpmno=13966 |language=ko }}</ref><ref name=\"nkle_KimN\"/>\n}}\n'''Kim Nung-o''' ({{lang|ko|\uae40\ub2a5\uc624}}, born in the late 1960s) is a [[North Korea]]n politician. He is the chairman of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] (WPK) Party Committee of [[Pyongyang]]. Kim is also a full member of the [[Central Committee of the WPK]] and an alternate member of [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|its Politburo]].\n\n==Career==\nKim Nung-o was born in the late 1960s. He was educated at [[Kim Il-sung University]].<ref name=\"nkle_KimN\">{{Cite web |title=Kim Nung O |work=North Korea Leadership Watch |access-date=21 March 2019 |url= http://www.nkleadershipwatch.org/leadership-biographies/kim-nung-o/ |date=28 February 2018 }}</ref>\n\nKim has worked at various departments of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea]] (WPK), being a vice director of the [[Finance and Accounting Department]] in 2013. He was first mentioned by [[North Korean media]] on 1 November 2014 when he was accompanying [[Kim Jong-un]] on a [[guidance tour]] of [[Pyongyang International Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=November: Military and diplomatic focus, status of Kim\u2019s family |last=Grisafi |first=John G. |work=NK News |date=8 December 2014 |access-date=21 March 2019 |url= https://www.nknews.org/2014/12/november-military-and-diplomatic-focus-status-of-kims-family/ }}</ref> Kim Nung-o became the chief secretary of the Party Committee of [[North Pyongan Province]] in December 2015, replacing [[Ri Man-gon]]. He subsequently become the chairman of the Party Committee.<ref name=\"nkle_KimN\"/> He now serves as the chairman of the Party Committee of the capital [[Pyongyang]].<ref name=kyodonews>{{Cite web |title=North Koreans vow to fulfill tasks Kim Jong Un cited in New Year statement |agency=Kyodo News |date=4 January 2019 |access-date=21 March 2019 |url= https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2019/01/3bb367ad7210-north-koreans-vow-to-fulfill-tasks-kim-jong-un-mentioned-in-new-year-statement.html }}</ref>\n\nKim became a full member of the Central Committee and an alternate member of the [[Politburo of the WPK]] at the [[7th Congress of the WPK]] in May 2016.<ref name=\"nkle_KimN\"/> In January 2019, Kim gave a speech at a mass rally at [[Kim Il-sung Square]] in Pyongyang,<ref name=kyodonews/> praising Kim Jong-un's New Year Address and urging inhabitants of the city to increase efforts to attain a self-reliant socialist economy.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Pyongyang citizens rally in support of Supreme Leader\u2019s address |agency=KCNA |work=The Pyongyang Times |date= |access-date=21 March 2019 |url= http://www.pyongyangtimes.com.kp/?bbs=28714 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|North Korea}}\n* [[Politics of North Korea]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kim Pyong-hae]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairman of WPK North Pyongyan Provincial Committee|years=2016-2018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mun Kyong-dok]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Choe Ryong-hae]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairman of WPK Pyongyang Provincial Committee|years=2018\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kim Yong-hwan (politician)|Kim Yong-hwan]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kim, Nung-o}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:North Korean politicians]]\n[[Category:1960s births]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kim_Nung-o"}
{"title_page": "Rob Flello", "text_new": "{{short description|British Liberal Democrat politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Rob Flello\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = \n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]]\n| parliament =\n| predecessor = [[George Stevenson (MP)|George Stevenson]]\n| successor = [[Jack Brereton]]\n| term_start = 5 May 2005\n| term_end = 5 May 2017 \n| birth_name = Robert Charles Douglas Flello \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1966|1|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Birmingham]], England\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] until September 2019\n[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Wales, Bangor]]\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| majority =\n|}}\n\n'''Robert Charles Douglas Flello''' (born 14 January 1966) is a British [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician who was [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]  [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]] from 2005 to 2017.  He lost his seat at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] to [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] candidate [[Jack Brereton]].\n\n==Early life==\nFlello was born in [[Bournville]], [[Birmingham]]. He attended [[Bournville Junior School|Bournville Junior]] and Infant schools before going to [[King's Norton Boys' School]]. At age 18 he went to [[University of Wales, Bangor]] to read Chemistry. He graduated in 1987 with a B.Sc (Hons).\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating, Flello worked for a short time at [[Cadbury]] in [[Bournville]] before joining the [[Inland Revenue]]. In 1989 he left to join [[Price Waterhouse]] accountants as a personal tax advisor. In 1995 he moved to [[Arthur Andersen]]. In 1999, he co-founded Platts Flello Limited, tax and financial advisors. In late 2003 he left to work as the CEO of Malachi Community Trust until December 2004.\n\n==Political career==\nFlello was elected as a councillor to the [[Longbridge]] ward of [[Birmingham City Council]] in 2002, stepping down in 2004. He is a former chairman of the [[Birmingham Northfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Northfield]] [[Constituency Labour Party]]. He served as a governor at the [[Newman University, Birmingham|Newman College]] in [[Bartley Green]], and was Chair of Governors for both Colmers Farm infants and junior schools. He was also a governor at The Meadows primary school. He served as a regional organiser for the Labour Party in 2004 until his election to [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\n===Parliament===\nFlello was elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]] following the retirement of [[George Stevenson (MP)|George Stevenson]]. Flello held the seat with a majority of 8,681 and made his [[maiden speech]] on 19 May 2005.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/cm050519/debtext/50519-20.htm#50519-20_spnew0 House of Commons Hansard Debates for 19 May 2005 (pt 20)]. Publications.parliament.uk (19 May 2005); retrieved 9 May 2015.</ref>\n\nIn parliament he was a member of the [[Science and Technology Select Committee]]. While Labour were in government he served as [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] first to the [[Lord Chancellor]], [[Charles Falconer, Baron Falconer of Thoroton]], then to the [[Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]], [[Hazel Blears]], and finally after 2009 to the [[Secretary of State for Defence]], [[Bob Ainsworth]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nIn June 2016, Labour Party activists in Stoke-on-Trent South proposed a motion of no confidence in Flello after he called on Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] to \"do the decent thing and resign\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/labour-activists-propose-motion-of-no-confidence-in-rob-flello-mp-as-he-called-on-corbyn-to-resign/story-29454491-detail/story.html|title=Labour activists propose motion of no confidence in Rob Flello MP as he called on Corbyn to resign|date=29 June 2016|website=Stoke Sentinel}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He had supported [[Owen Smith]] in the failed attempt to replace [[Jeremy Corbyn]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election|2016 Labour leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|title=Full list of MPs and MEPs backing challenger Owen Smith|date=2016-07-21|website=LabourList|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 he defected to the Lib Dems and was selected as their parliamentary candidate for his old seat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/stoke-on-trent-news/look-whos-back-former-potteries-3524124|title=Former Stoke-on-Trent Labour MP Rob Flello to fight old seat \u2013 as a Lib Dem|last=Corrigan|first=Phil|date=12 November 2019|website=Stoke Sentinel}}</ref> 36 hours after his selection, however, the Lib Dems deselected Flello, citing \"how greatly his values diverge from ours\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/stoke-on-trent-news/cut-short-former-stoke-trent-3531744|title=Cut short! Lib Dems deselect former Labour MP Rob Flello after just 36 hours|first=Joe|last=Burn|date=12 November 2019|website=Stoke Sentinel}}</ref> It is believed that they objected to his socially conservative views on abortion and same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-stoke-staffordshire-50401318|title=Former Labour MP deselected as Lib Dem candidate|date=13 November 2019|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Social views===\nFlello is a convert to Catholicism and stated in 2014 \"I could no more leave my faith at the door of the House of Commons than I could my name or my gender or my arms and legs\". He was a member of the anti-abortion All-Party Parliamentary Pro-Life Group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/commentandblogs/2017/06/09/this-was-a-grim-night-for-christians-and-pro-lifers-in-parliament/|title=This was a grim night for Christians and pro-lifers in parliament - CatholicHerald.co.uk|date=9 June 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Flello also opposes [[Same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom|same-sex marriage]] and was one of the few Labour MPs to vote against the [[Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act 2013]], citing his religious views.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/01/20/labour-shadow-justice-minister-rob-flello-to-vote-against-same-sex-marriage-equality/|title=Labour Shadow Justice Minister Rob Flello to vote against same-sex marriage equality|publisher=[[PinkNews]]}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2007 Flello was accused of [[filibuster]]ing a fellow Labour backbencher's [[Private Members' Bills in the Parliament of the United Kingdom|private members bill]]. The bill, introduced by neighbouring Staffordshire MP [[Paul Farrelly]], aimed to give temporary and agency workers similar employment rights to permanent staff. It was backed by the [[Unite the Union|Unite]] trade union. The incident provoked an angry response in the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2007/03/07/shame-of-mouthy-mp-115875-18716285|title=SHAME OF MOUTHY MP|date=7 March 2007|work=mirror.co.uk|accessdate=13 January 2013}}{{better source|date=March 2017|reason=Tabloids are not acceptable sources for [[WP:BLP]]s}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Flello blamed \"shocking congestion\" in London on the loss of tarmac from building cycle lanes, which received a critical response from bike charity the [[London Cycling Campaign]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Batchelor|first1=Tom|title=MP says cycle lanes should be scrapped to make more room for cars|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-mp-rob-flello-comment-blame-cycle-lanes-for-city-traffic-transport-select-committee-a7519561.html|work=The Independent|date=10 January 2017}}</ref> and cycling website road.cc,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowden|first1=Alex|title=Senior MP asks whether 'loss of tarmac' for cycle lanes is causing London's congestion problems as Government launches urban congestion inquiry|url=http://road.cc/content/news/215325-senior-mp-asks-whether-loss-tarmac-cycle-lanes-causing-londons-congestion|work=road.cc|date=10 January 2017}}</ref> both pointing out that tarmac had been repurposed to another form of transport and that the increased number of journeys overall in Central London were what was causing congestion, not the segregated cycle tracks that are on less than 1%<ref>{{cite web|last1=RH|first1=Andrew|title=24 London Boroughs installed ZERO segregated cycle-lanes since the last London elections.|url=http://stopkillingcyclists.org/2014/04/02/press-release-wall-of-death-24-london-boroughs-installed-zero-segregated-cycle-lanes-since-the-last-london-elections/|website=SKC|date=2 April 2014}}</ref> of London roads.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.robertflello.com}}\n*{{UK MP links|parliament=rob-flello/1569|publicwhip=rob_flello|theywork=rob_flello}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[George Stevenson (MP)|George Stevenson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jack Brereton]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Labour Party shadow cabinet election, 2010}}\n{{West Midlands Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flello, Robert}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Bangor University]]\n[[Category:British Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:British anti-abortion activists]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Liberal Democrat politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Rob Flello\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = \n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]]\n| parliament =\n| predecessor = [[George Stevenson (MP)|George Stevenson]]\n| successor = [[Jack Brereton]]\n| term_start = 5 May 2005\n| term_end = 5 May 2017 \n| birth_name = Robert Charles Douglas Flello \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1966|1|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Birmingham]], England\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] until September 2019\n[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Wales, Bangor]]\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| majority =\n|}}\n\n'''Robert Charles Douglas Flello''' (born 14 January 1966) is a British [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician who was [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]  [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]] from 2005 to 2017.  He lost his seat at the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]] to [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] candidate [[Jack Brereton]].\n\n==Early life==\nFlello was born in [[Bournville]], [[Birmingham]]. He attended [[Bournville Junior School|Bournville Junior]] and Infant schools before going to [[King's Norton Boys' School]]. At age 18 he went to [[University of Wales, Bangor]] to read Chemistry. He graduated in 1987 with a B.Sc (Hons).\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating, Flello worked for a short time at [[Cadbury]] in [[Bournville]] before joining the [[Inland Revenue]]. In 1989 he left to join [[Price Waterhouse]] accountants as a personal tax advisor. In 1995 he moved to [[Arthur Andersen]]. In 1999, he co-founded Platts Flello Limited, tax and financial advisors. In late 2003 he left to work as the CEO of Malachi Community Trust until December 2004.\n\n==Political career==\nFlello was elected as a councillor to the [[Longbridge]] ward of [[Birmingham City Council]] in 2002, stepping down in 2004. He is a former chairman of the [[Birmingham Northfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Northfield]] [[Constituency Labour Party]]. He served as a governor at the [[Newman University, Birmingham|Newman College]] in [[Bartley Green]], and was Chair of Governors for both Colmers Farm infants and junior schools. He was also a governor at The Meadows primary school. He served as a regional organiser for the Labour Party in 2004 until his election to [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\n===Parliament===\nFlello was elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]] following the retirement of [[George Stevenson (MP)|George Stevenson]]. Flello held the seat with a majority of 8,681 and made his [[maiden speech]] on 19 May 2005.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/cm050519/debtext/50519-20.htm#50519-20_spnew0 House of Commons Hansard Debates for 19 May 2005 (pt 20)]. Publications.parliament.uk (19 May 2005); retrieved 9 May 2015.</ref>\n\nIn parliament he was a member of the [[Science and Technology Select Committee]]. While Labour were in government he served as [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] first to the [[Lord Chancellor]], [[Charles Falconer, Baron Falconer of Thoroton]], then to the [[Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government]], [[Hazel Blears]], and finally after 2009 to the [[Secretary of State for Defence]], [[Bob Ainsworth]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nIn June 2016, Labour Party activists in Stoke-on-Trent South proposed a motion of no confidence in Flello after he called on Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] to \"do the decent thing and resign\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/labour-activists-propose-motion-of-no-confidence-in-rob-flello-mp-as-he-called-on-corbyn-to-resign/story-29454491-detail/story.html|title=Labour activists propose motion of no confidence in Rob Flello MP as he called on Corbyn to resign|date=29 June 2016|website=Stoke Sentinel}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He had supported [[Owen Smith]] in the failed attempt to replace [[Jeremy Corbyn]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|title=Full list of MPs and MEPs backing challenger Owen Smith|date=2016-07-21|website=LabourList|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 he defected to the Lib Dems and was selected as their parliamentary candidate for his old seat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/stoke-on-trent-news/look-whos-back-former-potteries-3524124|title=Former Stoke-on-Trent Labour MP Rob Flello to fight old seat \u2013 as a Lib Dem|last=Corrigan|first=Phil|date=12 November 2019|website=Stoke Sentinel}}</ref> 36 hours after his selection, however, the Lib Dems deselected Flello, citing \"how greatly his values diverge from ours\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/stoke-on-trent-news/cut-short-former-stoke-trent-3531744|title=Cut short! Lib Dems deselect former Labour MP Rob Flello after just 36 hours|first=Joe|last=Burn|date=12 November 2019|website=Stoke Sentinel}}</ref> It is believed that they objected to his socially conservative views on abortion and same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-stoke-staffordshire-50401318|title=Former Labour MP deselected as Lib Dem candidate|date=13 November 2019|publisher=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Social views===\nFlello is a convert to Catholicism and stated in 2014 \"I could no more leave my faith at the door of the House of Commons than I could my name or my gender or my arms and legs\". He was a member of the anti-abortion All-Party Parliamentary Pro-Life Group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/commentandblogs/2017/06/09/this-was-a-grim-night-for-christians-and-pro-lifers-in-parliament/|title=This was a grim night for Christians and pro-lifers in parliament - CatholicHerald.co.uk|date=9 June 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Flello also opposes [[Same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom|same-sex marriage]] and was one of the few Labour MPs to vote against the [[Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act 2013]], citing his religious views.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/01/20/labour-shadow-justice-minister-rob-flello-to-vote-against-same-sex-marriage-equality/|title=Labour Shadow Justice Minister Rob Flello to vote against same-sex marriage equality|publisher=[[PinkNews]]}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2007 Flello was accused of [[filibuster]]ing a fellow Labour backbencher's [[Private Members' Bills in the Parliament of the United Kingdom|private members bill]]. The bill, introduced by neighbouring Staffordshire MP [[Paul Farrelly]], aimed to give temporary and agency workers similar employment rights to permanent staff. It was backed by the [[Unite the Union|Unite]] trade union. The incident provoked an angry response in the ''[[Daily Mirror]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2007/03/07/shame-of-mouthy-mp-115875-18716285|title=SHAME OF MOUTHY MP|date=7 March 2007|work=mirror.co.uk|accessdate=13 January 2013}}{{better source|date=March 2017|reason=Tabloids are not acceptable sources for [[WP:BLP]]s}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Flello blamed \"shocking congestion\" in London on the loss of tarmac from building cycle lanes, which received a critical response from bike charity the [[London Cycling Campaign]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Batchelor|first1=Tom|title=MP says cycle lanes should be scrapped to make more room for cars|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-mp-rob-flello-comment-blame-cycle-lanes-for-city-traffic-transport-select-committee-a7519561.html|work=The Independent|date=10 January 2017}}</ref> and cycling website road.cc,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowden|first1=Alex|title=Senior MP asks whether 'loss of tarmac' for cycle lanes is causing London's congestion problems as Government launches urban congestion inquiry|url=http://road.cc/content/news/215325-senior-mp-asks-whether-loss-tarmac-cycle-lanes-causing-londons-congestion|work=road.cc|date=10 January 2017}}</ref> both pointing out that tarmac had been repurposed to another form of transport and that the increased number of journeys overall in Central London were what was causing congestion, not the segregated cycle tracks that are on less than 1%<ref>{{cite web|last1=RH|first1=Andrew|title=24 London Boroughs installed ZERO segregated cycle-lanes since the last London elections.|url=http://stopkillingcyclists.org/2014/04/02/press-release-wall-of-death-24-london-boroughs-installed-zero-segregated-cycle-lanes-since-the-last-london-elections/|website=SKC|date=2 April 2014}}</ref> of London roads.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.robertflello.com}}\n*{{UK MP links|parliament=rob-flello/1569|publicwhip=rob_flello|theywork=rob_flello}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[George Stevenson (MP)|George Stevenson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Stoke-on-Trent South (UK Parliament constituency)|Stoke-on-Trent South]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013[[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jack Brereton]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Labour Party shadow cabinet election, 2010}}\n{{West Midlands Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flello, Robert}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Bangor University]]\n[[Category:British Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:British anti-abortion activists]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) parliamentary candidates]]\n", "name_user": "TrottieTrue", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rob_Flello"}
